{"title_page": "Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!", "text_new": "{{ external media\n| width  = 210px\n| align  = right\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UFUtDdgEYwk Original video]\n}}\n\"'''Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!'''\" ({{lang-ru|\u0422\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439? \u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f!}}, meaning \"Who are you? Hey!, Goodbye!\") is a title of the [[viral video]], showing [[meykhana]] performance with repeating Russian [[Hook (music)|hook]] \"Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!\" by two brothers Intigam and Ehtiram Rustamov from [[Azerbaijan]]. The video was filmed on 5 November 2011 at a wedding in [[T\u0259ng\u0259rud|Tangarud]], [[Azerbaijan]] and was subsequently viewed over 10 million times on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UFUtDdgEYwk| title = \u0422\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439,\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439 \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f! (Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!)| publisher = [[YouTube]]| date = 2012-01-25| accessdate = 12 July 2012 }}</ref> It is sung in the form of [[flyting]] between Talysh and [[Baku]] groups in [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]], [[Talysh language|Talysh]] and Russian. The video was also viewed over 10 million times at theinstv, the YouTube channel of Insanity TV.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GZrGyySwmbM| title = \u0422\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439? \u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f! :D_5.mp4.mp4| publisher = [[YouTube]]| date = 2012-05-23| accessdate = 30 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n== Political references ==\n[[File:Serzh Sargsyan Davay, do svidaniya!.jpg|thumb|300px|Poster with the crossed-out portrait of Armenian president [[Serzh Sargsyan]] with the famous line during the [[2013 Armenian presidential election protests]] ]]\n\nThe hook itself was popularized particularly by the Russian Car Owners Federation official Andrey Filin, who had wrote on [[Twitter]]: \"Tomorrow I'll hang a sign on my car: '[[Vladimir Putin|Putin]], who are you? See you, goodbye'. I'll make people smile\".<ref name=\"TMT\">{{cite news | url = http://www.themoscowtimes.com/mobile/article/459562.html| title = Video Inspires Anti-Putin Twitter Trend| newspaper = [[The Moscow Times]]| date = 31 May 2012| accessdate = 14 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\nFilin's phrase \"Putin, who are you? Come on, goodbye\" was in turn propagated by the press secretary of [[Ilya Ponomarev]] and by the Russian art group [[Voina|Voyna]]. The Russian [[hashtag]] #\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0442\u044b\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439\u0434\u043e\u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f (\"Putin, who are you? Come on, goodbye\") began spreading in Twitter on 29 May 2012<ref name=\"TMT\"/> and entered Twitter's worldwide trends the next day. The phrase \"Who are you? See you, goodbye\" later appeared on [[Picketing (protest)|picket]] banners in [[Russia]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ntv.ru/novosti/305222/| script-title=ru:\u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f| language=Russian|publisher = [[NTV (Russia)|NTV]]| accessdate = 18 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2012, a group of [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] opposition members used the phrase \"Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!\" targeting president [[Mikheil Saakashvili]] in a performance of their own, which they sang in [[Georgian language|Georgian]] and released online.<ref>[http://vesti.az/news/127918/D098_D0B3D180D183D0B7D0B8D0BDD181D0BAD0B8D0B5_D0BED0BFD0BFD0BED0B7D0B8D186D0B8D0BED0BDD0B5D180D18B_D0B2D0B7D18FD0BBD0B8_D0BDD0B0_D0B2D0BED0BED180D183D0B6D0B5D0BDD0B8D0B5_D182D0B2D0BED180D187D0B5D181D182D0B2D0BE_D0B0D0B7D0B5D180D0B1D0B0D0B9D0B4D0B6D0B0D0BDD181D0BAD0B8D185_D0BCD0B5D0B9D185D0B0D0BDD189D0B8D0BAD0BED0B2_ \u0418 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u043f\u043f\u043e\u0437\u0438\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0440\u044b \u0432\u0437\u044f\u043b\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0430\u0437\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043c\u0435\u0439\u0445\u0430\u043d\u0449\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432]. ''Vesti.az''. 27 August 2012.</ref> The phrase addressed to the Hungarian government was used on placards posted around [[Yerevan]], [[Armenia]] during a protest at the Consulate of Hungary on 1 September 2012, upon the extradition of officer [[Ramil Safarov]], who had been convicted by a Hungarian court for murdering his Armenian counterpart in 2004.<ref>[http://www.argumenti.ru/world/2012/09/199662 Flag Burning by Hungarian Consulate]. AN Online. 1 September 2012.</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nThe hook \"Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!\" has been repeatedly [[remix]]ed and was [[Sampling (music)|sampled]] for [[dubstep]] and [[tech house]] [[Mashup (music)|mashup]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://muzofon.com/search/\u0422\u044b%20\u043a\u0442\u043e%20\u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439%20\u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439%20\u0434\u043e%20\u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140921225021/http://muzofon.com/search/%D0%A2%D1%8B%20%D0%BA%D1%82%D0%BE%20%D1%82%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%B9%20%D0%94%D0%B0%D0%B2%D0%B0%D0%B9%20%D0%B4%D0%BE%20%D1%81%D0%B2%D0%B8%D0%B4%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%8F| url-status = dead| archive-date = 21 September 2014| title = \u0422\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439 \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f| publisher = Muzofon| accessdate = 14 June 2012}}</ref> Russian rapper [[Timati]] sampled the hook for his [[diss song]] against [[Philipp Kirkorov]], with participants fashioning the dress style and locale of the original video.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M9RcdLCJkw4| title = #\u0414\u0410\u0412\u0410\u0419\u0414\u041e\u0421\u0412\u0418\u0414\u0410\u041d\u0418\u042f (OFFICIAL VIDEO)| publisher = YouTube| accessdate = 14 June 2012}}</ref>  \"Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!\" is also the subject of one of the sketches of Russian ''Lego Life Show'' on YouTube. The phrase also influenced an article on the Russian sports news website Sportbox, which wrote about the \"unpleasing list with trendy title \"Who are you? See you, goodbye!\" in connection with the group stage of [[UEFA Euro 2012]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.sportbox.ru/Vidy_sporta/Futbol/Euro-2012/spbnews_NI315468_Ispaniya-Irlandiya-Davay-do-svidaniya| script-title=ru:\u0418\u0441\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u2013 \u0418\u0440\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u044f: \u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f?| language=Russian|publisher = News.sportbox.ru| accessdate = 14 June 2012}}</ref> The phrase \"Who are you? See you, goodbye!\" was also uttered by Russian sportcaster Viktor Gusev during a [[UEFA Euro 2012 Group D#Ukraine vs Sweden|Euro 2012 match between Sweden and Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.newsazerbaijan.ru/sport/20120612/297452302.html| script-title=ru:\u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0413\u0443\u0441\u0435\u0432: \u0418\u0441\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0441\u043e\u043d, \"\u0442\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439, \u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f!\"| publisher = Newsazerbaijan| language=Russian|date=12 June 2012|accessdate = 14 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Viral videos]]\n[[Category:YouTube videos]]\n[[Category:Russian words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Political catchphrases]]\n[[Category:Words and phrases introduced in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 works]]\n[[Category:2011 in Azerbaijan]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in the 2010s]]\n", "text_old": "{{ external media\n| width  = 210px\n| align  = right\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UFUtDdgEYwk Original video]\n}}\n\"'''Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!'''\" ({{lang-ru|\u0422\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439? \u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f!}}, meaning \"Who are you? \n\n\nHey!, Goodbye!\") is a title of the [[viral video]], showing [[meykhana]] performance with repeating Russian [[Hook (music)|hook]] \"Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!\" by two brothers Intigam and Ehtiram Rustamov from [[Azerbaijan]]. The video was filmed on 5 November 2011 at a wedding in [[T\u0259ng\u0259rud|Tangarud]], [[Azerbaijan]] and was subsequently viewed over 10 million times on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UFUtDdgEYwk| title = \u0422\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439,\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439 \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f! (Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!)| publisher = [[YouTube]]| date = 2012-01-25| accessdate = 12 July 2012 }}</ref> It is sung in the form of [[flyting]] between Talysh and [[Baku]] groups in [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]], [[Talysh language|Talysh]] and Russian. The video was also viewed over 10 million times at theinstv, the YouTube channel of Insanity TV.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GZrGyySwmbM| title = \u0422\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439? \u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f! :D_5.mp4.mp4| publisher = [[YouTube]]| date = 2012-05-23| accessdate = 30 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n== Political references ==\n[[File:Serzh Sargsyan Davay, do svidaniya!.jpg|thumb|300px|Poster with the crossed-out portrait of Armenian president [[Serzh Sargsyan]] with the famous line during the [[2013 Armenian presidential election protests]] ]]\n\nThe hook itself was popularized particularly by the Russian Car Owners Federation official Andrey Filin, who had wrote on [[Twitter]]: \"Tomorrow I'll hang a sign on my car: '[[Vladimir Putin|Putin]], who are you? See you, goodbye'. I'll make people smile\".<ref name=\"TMT\">{{cite news | url = http://www.themoscowtimes.com/mobile/article/459562.html| title = Video Inspires Anti-Putin Twitter Trend| newspaper = [[The Moscow Times]]| date = 31 May 2012| accessdate = 14 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\nFilin's phrase \"Putin, who are you? Come on, goodbye\" was in turn propagated by the press secretary of [[Ilya Ponomarev]] and by the Russian art group [[Voina|Voyna]]. The Russian [[hashtag]] #\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0442\u044b\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439\u0434\u043e\u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f (\"Putin, who are you? Come on, goodbye\") began spreading in Twitter on 29 May 2012<ref name=\"TMT\"/> and entered Twitter's worldwide trends the next day. The phrase \"Who are you? See you, goodbye\" later appeared on [[Picketing (protest)|picket]] banners in [[Russia]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ntv.ru/novosti/305222/| script-title=ru:\u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f| language=Russian|publisher = [[NTV (Russia)|NTV]]| accessdate = 18 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2012, a group of [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] opposition members used the phrase \"Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!\" targeting president [[Mikheil Saakashvili]] in a performance of their own, which they sang in [[Georgian language|Georgian]] and released online.<ref>[http://vesti.az/news/127918/D098_D0B3D180D183D0B7D0B8D0BDD181D0BAD0B8D0B5_D0BED0BFD0BFD0BED0B7D0B8D186D0B8D0BED0BDD0B5D180D18B_D0B2D0B7D18FD0BBD0B8_D0BDD0B0_D0B2D0BED0BED180D183D0B6D0B5D0BDD0B8D0B5_D182D0B2D0BED180D187D0B5D181D182D0B2D0BE_D0B0D0B7D0B5D180D0B1D0B0D0B9D0B4D0B6D0B0D0BDD181D0BAD0B8D185_D0BCD0B5D0B9D185D0B0D0BDD189D0B8D0BAD0BED0B2_ \u0418 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u043f\u043f\u043e\u0437\u0438\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0440\u044b \u0432\u0437\u044f\u043b\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0430\u0437\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043c\u0435\u0439\u0445\u0430\u043d\u0449\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432]. ''Vesti.az''. 27 August 2012.</ref> The phrase addressed to the Hungarian government was used on placards posted around [[Yerevan]], [[Armenia]] during a protest at the Consulate of Hungary on 1 September 2012, upon the extradition of officer [[Ramil Safarov]], who had been convicted by a Hungarian court for murdering his Armenian counterpart in 2004.<ref>[http://www.argumenti.ru/world/2012/09/199662 Flag Burning by Hungarian Consulate]. AN Online. 1 September 2012.</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nThe hook \"Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!\" has been repeatedly [[remix]]ed and was [[Sampling (music)|sampled]] for [[dubstep]] and [[tech house]] [[Mashup (music)|mashup]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://muzofon.com/search/\u0422\u044b%20\u043a\u0442\u043e%20\u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439%20\u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439%20\u0434\u043e%20\u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140921225021/http://muzofon.com/search/%D0%A2%D1%8B%20%D0%BA%D1%82%D0%BE%20%D1%82%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%B9%20%D0%94%D0%B0%D0%B2%D0%B0%D0%B9%20%D0%B4%D0%BE%20%D1%81%D0%B2%D0%B8%D0%B4%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%8F| url-status = dead| archive-date = 21 September 2014| title = \u0422\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439 \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f| publisher = Muzofon| accessdate = 14 June 2012}}</ref> Russian rapper [[Timati]] sampled the hook for his [[diss song]] against [[Philipp Kirkorov]], with participants fashioning the dress style and locale of the original video.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M9RcdLCJkw4| title = #\u0414\u0410\u0412\u0410\u0419\u0414\u041e\u0421\u0412\u0418\u0414\u0410\u041d\u0418\u042f (OFFICIAL VIDEO)| publisher = YouTube| accessdate = 14 June 2012}}</ref>  \"Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!\" is also the subject of one of the sketches of Russian ''Lego Life Show'' on YouTube. The phrase also influenced an article on the Russian sports news website Sportbox, which wrote about the \"unpleasing list with trendy title \"Who are you? See you, goodbye!\" in connection with the group stage of [[UEFA Euro 2012]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.sportbox.ru/Vidy_sporta/Futbol/Euro-2012/spbnews_NI315468_Ispaniya-Irlandiya-Davay-do-svidaniya| script-title=ru:\u0418\u0441\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u2013 \u0418\u0440\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u044f: \u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f?| language=Russian|publisher = News.sportbox.ru| accessdate = 14 June 2012}}</ref> The phrase \"Who are you? See you, goodbye!\" was also uttered by Russian sportcaster Viktor Gusev during a [[UEFA Euro 2012 Group D#Ukraine vs Sweden|Euro 2012 match between Sweden and Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.newsazerbaijan.ru/sport/20120612/297452302.html| script-title=ru:\u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0413\u0443\u0441\u0435\u0432: \u0418\u0441\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0441\u043e\u043d, \"\u0442\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439, \u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f!\"| publisher = Newsazerbaijan| language=Russian|date=12 June 2012|accessdate = 14 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Viral videos]]\n[[Category:YouTube videos]]\n[[Category:Russian words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Political catchphrases]]\n[[Category:Words and phrases introduced in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 works]]\n[[Category:2011 in Azerbaijan]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in the 2010s]]\n", "name_user": "Zealander", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ty_kto_takoy%3F_Davay,_do_svidaniya!"}
{"title_page": "Allan Jones (businessman)", "text_new": "{{short description|American businessman}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name = Allan Jones\n| image = Photo of Allan Jones.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = December 31, 1952\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = \n| nationality =\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education = [[Cleveland High School (Tennessee)|Cleveland High School]]\n| alma mater = [[Middle Tennessee State University]]\n| employer = \n| occupation = Businessman\n| title =\n| salary = \n| networth = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party =\n| boards = \n| religion =\n| spouse = Candy Robinson (1972-75)<br/>Janie Pangle (m. 1983)\n| children = 4\n| relatives = \n}}\n'''William Allan Jones Jr.''' (born December 31, 1952) is an American businessman from [[Cleveland, Tennessee]].  He is the founder, chairman, and CEO of [[Check Into Cash]], Creditcorp, Jones Management Services, and the Community Financial Services Association, as well as several other local [[loan|lending agencies]].<ref name=woop>{{cite news|last=Pendergrass|first=Toby|date=April 1, 2011|title=WOOP Investigates The Truth about Allan Jones|url=http://www.woopfm.com/a_jones_Story.htm|work=[[WOOP-FM]]|location=Cleveland, Tennessee|access-date=October 24, 2011}}</ref><ref name=BBB>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbb.org/us/tn/memphis/profile/consumer-finance-companies/check-into-cash-0543-33007054|title=Check Into Cash &#124; Better Business Bureau\u00ae Profile|website=www.bbb.org}}</ref><ref name=JMS>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jonesmanagement.com/welcome.htm |title=Jones Management Services |access-date=June 6, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316051721/http://www.jonesmanagement.com/welcome.htm |archive-date=March 16, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He has been called the \"father of the payday loan industry\" for founding and building the first major [[payday loan]] chain.<ref name=harpers>{{cite web|url=http://harpers.org/archive/2009/04/usury-country/|title=Usury Country &#124; Harper&#039;s Magazine|publisher=harpers.org|accessdate=March 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nJones was born on December 31, 1952, in Cleveland, Tennessee to William A. (Bill) Jones (1919\u20131981) and Virginia Slaughter Jones (1925\u20132003).<ref name=gen/>\n\nJones attended [[Cleveland High School (Tennessee)|Cleveland High School]], where he wrestled and won various awards and served as team captain.<ref name=woop /> He graduated in 1972. Jones credited wrestling with helping build character: \"In wrestling, I didn't have anyone to rely on but me.\" He declined wrestling scholarships to pursue a business degree at [[Middle Tennessee State University]].<ref name=matt>''The Mat''. \"Allan Jones Donates $1 Million to Build Wrestling Facilities\" by Sandra Rowland, May 23, 2001</ref>\n\n== Business career ==\n===Early career===\nJones left college at age 20 to help his father stabilize the family's small business, the Credit Bureau of Cleveland.<ref name=timesfp>Chattanooga Times Free Press, February 24, 2008</ref> He purchased this reporting and debt collection business in 1977 and developed it to become one of the largest credit bureau databases in the state.<ref name=cash />\n\nJones sold the credit reporting side of the business to [[Equifax]] in 1988, although he retained the name and the company's collection agency division. He then built the company to be the largest in Tennessee with offices from Memphis to Atlanta. Jones sold the company in 1998.<ref name=power />\n\nJones founded Check Into Cash in 1993. The idea arose from him seeing a former credit bureau manager who was operating out of a small service station and cashing checks with the agreement that the owner would hold the checks until the next payday before submitting them to the bank. Check Into Cash eventually grew to include 1,300 stores nationwide.<ref name=woop />\n\n=== Check Into Cash ===\n[[File:Check Into Cash store.jpg|thumb|Check Into Cash store.]]\nJones' research revealed the market for small, short term, fee-based loans collateralized by the customer's signature, leading him to found Check Into Cash in 1993.<ref name=cash /> The business model was made possible after Jones allegedly donated large amounts of money to multiple state legislators in order to convince them to change laws that previously prohibited charging of what some have characterized as [[predatory lending|exorbitant interest rate]]s.<ref name=latimes/> In effect, Jones' critics charged that he bought the State legislation that allows him to do business.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brook|first=Daniel|title=Usury country: Welcome to the birthplace of payday lending|journal=Harper's Magazine|date=April 2009|url=http://harpers.org/archive/2009/04/0082451|accessdate=January 7, 2012}}</ref> {{As of|2005}} Check Into Cash was the second largest [[payday loan]] company in the US and was planning to expand on its existing 1,300 locations.<ref name=cash />\n\n=== Community Financial Services Association ===\nJones has been credited with founding the [[Community Financial Services Association of America]], or CFSA in 1999.<ref name=woop /> CFSA is the national trade association for companies that offer small-dollar, short-term loans or payday advances. Through a code of \"Best Practices,\" CFSA members pledge to abide by responsible industry practices that ensure customers understand the cost and risk of short-term payday advances to facilitate the best financial decisions. The practices also require that members hold themselves \"to the highest standard of service\".<ref name=cfsa>[http://cfsaa.com/about-cfsa.aspx \"About CFSA\"], Community Financial Services Association of America</ref>\n\nJones said he founded CFSA after breaking away from the National Check Cashers Association, due to concerns that the NCCA, now called Financial Service Centers of America, was not giving enough attention to the payday lending industry.<ref name=woop />\n\n=== Hardwick Clothes ===\n[[File:Photo of C L Hardwick.jpg|thumb|150px|C.L. Hardwick, founder of Hardwick Clothes]]\n\nIn 2014, Jones purchased [[Hardwick Clothes]], a company founded in Cleveland, in 1880. Hardwick Clothes is the oldest manufacturer of tailor-made clothing in the United States.<ref name=hardwicksale>{{cite news|title=Sewing up the deal |newspaper=Cleveland Banner |date=June 20, 2014 |url=http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/25322373/article-Sewing-up-the-deal |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718181706/http://clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/25322373/article-Sewing-up-the-deal |archivedate=July 18, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nHardwick Clothes, which began as Cleveland Woolen Mills, was one of two companies founded by C.L. Hardwick in the 19th century. Hardwick put his son Joseph in charge of Hardwick Stove, the family's other business, while his son George ran the clothing company. Cleveland Woolen Mills soon evolved into a manufacturing plant, making suits and other items of apparel.<ref name=hardwickhistory>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Fletcher|title=A history of our supplier, Hardwick Clothes|url=http://seersuckerandtweeds.net/2011/06/14/127/|accessdate=July 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812153111/http://seersuckerandtweeds.net/2011/06/14/127/|archive-date=August 12, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Hardwick Stove was absorbed into [[Maytag]] in 1981.\n\nThe company, known for its \"Sewn in the South\" slogan and renowned during the 1960s for making the world's best blazer, was facing bankruptcy when Jones acquired it. Jones has said he was attracted to Hardwick Clothes because it was the oldest business of its kind in America, and is convinced that the American consumer pendulum is swinging back to \"made in America.\"<ref name=hardwickhistory />\n\nWithin weeks of purchasing Hardwick Clothes, Jones named Bruce Bellusci, former executive vice president at Hart Schafner & Marx, the company's new CEO/president.<ref name=brucebellusci>{{cite news|title=Bruce Bellusci Is New President Of Hardwick Clothes|newspaper=The Chattanoogan|date=July 23, 2014|url=http://www.chattanoogan.com/2014/7/23/280948/Bruce-Bellusci-Is-New-President-Of.aspx}}</ref> He also recruited Hart's designer, engineer, and three top salesmen to Hardwick.\n\nIn September 2017, Jones made national headlines when he announced that Hardwick Clothes, Check Into Cash and his other companies would no longer advertise during NFL games as a response to the [[U.S. national anthem protests (2016\u2013present)|national anthem protests]] by the league's players, which the businessman called \"unpatriotic behavior.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=September 27, 2017 |title=Cleveland Businessman Allan Jones Pulls NFL Ads After National Anthem Snub |url=http://www.chattanoogan.com/2017/9/27/355672/Cleveland-Businessman-Allan-Jones-Pulls.aspx |work=Chattanoogan |location= |access-date=November 3, 2017 }}</ref> Jones was featured on the [[Fox Business Network]] discussing the decision.<ref>{{cite AV media |people= |date=September 29, 2017|title=Tennessee business owner on pulling ads from NFL|trans-title= |medium= |language= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cfR3p4GHWPI|access-date=November 19, 2017|format=Video|time= |location= |publisher=Fox Business |id= |isbn= |oclc= |quote= |ref=}}</ref>\n\nJones sold Hardwick in December 2019 to the company Puerto Rico Industries for the Blind.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesfreepress.com/news/business/aroundregion/story/2019/dec/16/americas-oldest-suit-maker-hnew-ownerpuerrico/510722/|title=Hardwick Clothes in Cleveland acquired by Puerto Rico nonprofit, will add 100 workers|website=timesfreepress.com|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\n===Other business ventures===\nJones is the largest property owner in [[Bradley County, Tennessee|Bradley County]] and has renovated many buildings, including a former shopping mall that he altered to become a site for his companies.<ref name=woop />\n\nThe Cleveland/Bradley Chamber of Commerce awarded Jones with the M.C. Headrick Free Enterprise Award, the organization's highest honor in 2003.<ref name=woop /> That same year Jones was inducted into the [[University of Tennessee at Chattanooga]]\u2019s Entrepreneurship Hall of Fame.<ref name=utc>[http://www.utc.edu/Academic/HarrisChair/2003.php \"Entrepreneurship Hall of Fame, 2003\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110308065748/http://www.utc.edu/Academic/HarrisChair/2003.php |date=March 8, 2011 }}, October 2003.</ref>\n\nJones was included on ''BusinessTN'' magazine's \"Power 100\" list in 2005.<ref name=power>''BusinessTN'', July 2005.</ref> Jones appeared on the cover of ''BusinessTN'' Magazine and was characterized as \"The King of Cash\". The magazine ranked Jones as one of the 20 wealthiest people in Tennessee.<ref name=cash>Drew Ruble, [http://businesstn.com/content/king-cash \"The King of Cash\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110825202735/http://businesstn.com/content/king-cash |date=August 25, 2011 }}, ''BusinessTN'', July 2005</ref>\n\nIn addition to Check Into Cash, Jones has founded or purchased several affiliate agencies, including U.S. Money Shops, a [[Pawnbroker|pawn agency]], LendingFrog.com, an online lending agency, Loan By Phone, and Buy Here Pay Here USA, a [[used car]] [[car loan|finance dealer]].<ref name=times>{{cite news |last=Green|first=Alex |date=February 5, 2015 |title=The Lord of Loans: How Cleveland payday-loan pioneer Allan Jones was propelled to fame and fortune |url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/business/aroundregion/story/2015/feb/05/lord-loans-how-clevelands-payday-loan-pioneer-allan-jones-was-propelled-fame-and-fortune/286693/|work=[[Chattanooga Times Free Press]] |location= |access-date=November 3, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n== High school wrestling support ==\n[[File:Jones_Wrestling_Center.jpg|thumb|200px|Jones Wrestling Center]]\n[[File:Allan jones wrestling.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Jones, far left, inside the Jones Wrestling Center.]]\n\nJones is the largest individual supporter of high school wrestling in the United States.{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}} He founded the Cleveland/Bradley Wrestling Club in 1990,<ref name=autogenerated1>''The Mat'', \"Allan Jones Donates A Million Dollars\", by Sandra Rowland, May 23, 2001.</ref> and provided the $1.3 million funding for the Jones Wrestling Center located on the Cleveland High School campus.<ref name=\"woop\"/> The clubs have been successful, with Jones remarking that \u201cIt has very little to do with the buildings and it has everything to do with the right coaches.\u201d<ref name=\"woop\"/>\n\nIn the 2013 state championship, Cleveland beat runner-up Wilson Central 78-4, setting a TSSAA record for the most lopsided margin of victory, most pins and quickest championship. Since the 2006-07 season, the wrestling team has won state championships in 2011, 2013 and 2014, 2015, and 2018.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Cleveland Daily Banner |title=Wrestling center gets funding for addition |url=http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/24750591/article-Wrestling-center-gets-funding-for-addition |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129075249/http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/24750591/article-Wrestling-center-gets-funding-for-addition |archivedate=November 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Jones received national attention when he auctioned off a 2009 King Ranch [[F-150]] four-wheel drive pickup truck autographed twice by President [[George W. Bush]]. The proceeds of the auction went to benefit Cleveland's Higher Calling Youth Wrestling Club and the National Wrestling Hall of Fame Dan Gable Museum. \n<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Cleveland Daily Banner |title=Jones puts Bush\u2019s truck on auction block |url=http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/jones-puts-bushs-truck-on-auction-block,55603  }}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropy ==\n[[File:Allan Jones Aquatic Center.jpg|thumb|Allan Jones Aquatic Center]]\n\nJones has been described as \"Cleveland\u2019s most celebrated benefactor.\"<ref name=cash />\n\nIn 1990, Jones founded MainStreet Cleveland, dedicated to the revitalization and promotion of Cleveland's historic downtown area and donated the funds for the construction of the Virgil F. Carmichael addition to the Cleveland Public Library.<ref name=woop /> He also wrote and funded Cleveland's Shade Tree Ordinance that helped the city's tree board earn the designation of Tennessee Tree Board of the Year in 2010.  Many of the trees that line the city's streets were donated by his foundation. He donated $4 million to the [[University of Tennessee]] at Knoxville for construction of a new Allan Jones Aquatic Center.<ref name=cash />\n\nIn 2011, Allan Jones contributed to the non-profit organization [[tnAchieves]], enabling it to launch its scholarship and mentoring program in all three Bradley County high schools, ensuring that every graduating senior from Cleveland High School, [[Walker Valley High School]], and [[Bradley Central High School]] had the opportunity to attend [[Cleveland State Community College]].<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Carroll |title=Cleveland, Bradley Students Get College Tuition Help |publisher=WRCBtv.com |date=August 4, 2011 |url=http://www.wrcbtv.com/story/15212583/cleveland-bradley-students-get-college-tuition-help|accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> In 2015, Jones was awarded the first-ever honorary degree from Cleveland State during its 49th Commencement Ceremony where he was the keynote speaker. A few days later, Jones received the Chancellor's Award for Excellence in Philanthropy from the Tennessee Board of Regents.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cleveland State Honors Allan Jones with Philanthropy Award|url=http://www.clevelandstatecc.edu/news/article/cleveland-state-honors-allan-jones-with-philanthropy-award|website=www.clevelandstateecc.edu|access-date=March 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417070827/http://www.clevelandstatecc.edu/news/article/cleveland-state-honors-allan-jones-with-philanthropy-award|archive-date=April 17, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Jones received the prestigious Fred Gregg Jr. award from the Greater Chattanooga Sports Hall of Fame for significant contributions to sports.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gregg Award going to Jones|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/sports/local/story/2012/feb/12/gregg-award-going-to-jones/70496/|website=www.timesfreepress.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the Jones family gave a donation to Lee University to purchase the old First Baptist Church building in downtown Cleveland and renovate it into a music performance hall. The building was named \u201cPangle Hall\u201d in honor of Jones' wife Janie Pangle Jones. Lee University President [[Paul Conn]] said Pangle Hall was only possible due to this donation.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Lee to dedicate Pangle Hall with student, faculty, alumni music |url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/chattanooganow/music/story/2014/oct/23/lee-dedicate-pangle-hall-student-faculty-alumni-mu/270183/ |work=Times Free Press |location=Chattanooga, Tennessee |date=October 23, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Jones made national headlines after he donated 43,000 pairs of eclipse-viewing sunglasses to students in six Tennessee school systems. The businessman said the donation was made to ensure students who wanted to view the solar eclipse did so only with safe, NASA-approved glasses.\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Protect those eyes! Businessman focused on kids\u2019 safety|url= http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/protect-those-eyes,63715|website=www.clevelandbanner.com}}</ref>\n\n== Tall Betsy ==\n{{main|Tall Betsy}}\n[[File:Photo_of_Tall_Betsy,_Fort_Hill_Cemetery,_1993.jpg|thumb|Photo of Tall Betsy in Fort Hill Cemetery, 1993.]]\nJones is credited with the creation of the legend of [[Tall Betsy]], a [[Halloween]] cultural icon based in Bradley County.\n\nJones based the character on stories (local folklore) that were told to his mother, Virginia Slaughter Jones, by her mother, Marie Schultz Slaughter. Virginia and other Cleveland children being raised during the 1930s were told by their parents that if they failed to come home before dark they would likely encounter Tall Betsy, sometimes called Black Betsy or simply \"The Lady in Black.\"<ref>Woop FM.com, April 1, 2011, \u201cWOOP Investigates the Legend of Tall Betsy\u201d</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Jones' home on [[Centenary Avenue Historic District|Centenary Avenue]] was the site of a Halloween world record. According to media reports, the Jones family handed out 11,201 pieces of bubblegum from 5 pm to 8 pm.<ref name=\"site3\">[http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/tall-betsy-set-to-appearat-block-party-730-pm,21130 Tall Betsy to Appear at Block Party], Cleveland Daily Banner, Official Site. Retrieved October 30, 2015.</ref>\n\nTall Betsy last appeared in 1998 after drawing a Halloween crowd of 25,000, although no explanation was ever given for the goblin's disappearance. Jones later told a reporter that while the goblin may have vanished, her spirit is embedded in the hearts and minds of the Cleveland residents who saw Tall Betsy during the eighteen years from 1980 to 1998.\n\nThe 2005 Block Party was dedicated in honor of Tall Betsy's 25th anniversary. The Block Party drew the largest crowd in the event's history. Jones arranged for nationally recognized celebrities such as the cast of \"Leave It To Beaver\" and Little Richard to entertain the more than 30,000 attendees. The Tennessee legislature declared Tall Betsy the official Halloween goblin of Bradley County in 1989. In 2011 the character was the subject of a documentary film.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Cleveland Daily Banner |title='Tall Betsy' returning to life in documentary |date=October 13, 2011 |url=http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/15846428/article-%E2%80%98Tall-Betsy%E2%80%99-returning-to-life-in-documentary |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121127164633/http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/15846428/article-%E2%80%98Tall-Betsy%E2%80%99-returning-to-life-in-documentary |archivedate=November 27, 2012 |accessdate=August 12, 2015}}</ref> In 2014, Jones\u2019 son, Bailey, assumed the identity of Tall Betsy and has appeared as the goblin each year at Halloween.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tall Betsy Set to Appear at Block Party|url=http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/tall-betsy-set-to-appearat-block-party-730-pm,21130|website=clevelandbanner.com}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism and controversy ==\n\nJones\u2019 company Check Into Cash has received criticism for its high interest rates and for harming its customers. Most believe that payday loans target those of low-income.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bestcompany.com/payday-loans/company/check-into-cash|title=Check Into Cash Reviews - Real Customer Reviews|work=Best Company|access-date=January 15, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nThe April 28, 2010, episode of [[MSNBC]]'s ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show]]'', had a segment about the payday loan industry. Maddow criticized Jones for charging people high interest rates.<ref name=\"msnbc\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.com/transcripts/rachel-maddow-show/2010-04-28|title=The Rachel Maddow Show, Transcript 04/28/10|work=MSNBC|access-date=October 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2010 interview with ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', when asked about the lack of diversity in his hometown of Cleveland, Jones allegedly said, \u201cWe have just enough blacks to put together a decent basketball team \u2014 but not so many the good people of Cleveland, Tennessee need to worry about crime. That\u2019s why I can leave my keys in the car with the door unlocked\u201d.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/gary-rivlin/portrait-of-a-subprime-le_b_602182.html|title=Portrait of a Subprime Lender: Allan Jones, Payday King|last=Rivlin|first=Gary|date=June 6, 2010|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> He noted that many of his company managers and friends are African Americans. The article cited an anonymous source who claimed some company employees referred to a black man who shines shoes as the \"Little Chocolate Man\u201d although no source for the comment was ever provided.<ref name=\":1\" /> Also in that interview, a former employee of Jones' company stated that Jones\u2019 barber shop was successful because of \u201cfemale barbers with big titties.\u201d<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/news/story/2010/jun/21/check-into-cash-founder-jones-denies-racial/20871/|title=Check into Cash founder Jones denies racial remarks|last=Report|first=Staff|date=June 21, 2010|website=Times Free Press|language=en-US|access-date=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJones denied ever making the statements to numerous media outlets and claimed he was misquoted, stating \"I gave generously of my time\u2026to assist in the preparation for writing a book, purported to fairly represent the credit needs of the middle income working population and the markets that serve them. Unfortunately, (the author) has chosen to rearrange some of my remarks to draw incorrect conclusions regarding my personal views and beliefs.\"<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n===Legal issues===\nJones was indicted on federal charges of [[wiretapping]] in 1975 after he placed a recording device on his first wife's telephone in October 1974 after she had been granted a [[restraining order]] against him, allegedly to determine if she was having an extramarital affair, which she reportedly was. Jones reportedly used information from the recordings to obtain a divorce. His indictment was dismissed by the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Tennessee|local district court]] before Jones could go to trial, and this dismissal was subsequently upheld by the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]] in 1976.<ref>{{cite court|litigants=United States of America, Plaintiff-Appellant, v. William Allan Jones Jr., Defendant-Appellee.|vol=542|reporter=F.2d|opinion=661|pinpoint=|court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]]|date=1976|url=https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/339314/united-states-v-william-allan-jones/|accessdate=2019-03-03|quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe legality of Jones' payday loan model was challenged shortly after Check into Cash was founded.<ref name=checkhistory>{{cite news|last=Bowers|first=Larry C.|date=July 12, 2018|title=Jones reflects on \u2018Check\u2019 history\n|url=http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/allan-jones-interview,83354|work=Cleveland Daily Banner|location=Cleveland, Tennessee|access-date=2019-03-03}}</ref> Initially Jones and other payday lenders claimed that the fee charged did not constitute interest, and therefore did not violate laws capping a maximum interest on loans, which runs contrary to multiple federal laws.<ref name=latimes/> In 1997 Check Into Cash was sued in a [[class-action lawsuit]] by two Cleveland attorneys, representing multiple customers, alleging violation of the [[Truth in Lending Act]] and [[Fair Debt Collection Act]], as well as other illegal practices. Check Into Cash eventually settled the case by paying $2.2 million to the class and $500,000 in attorneys' fees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.in.gov/dfi/2366.htm|title=The Growth of Legal Loan Sharking: A Report on the Payday Loan Industry|last=Fox|first=Jean Ann|date=November 1998|website=in.gov|publisher=Consumer Federation of America|access-date=2019-03-03|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20170410211246/https://www.in.gov/dfi/2366.htm|archivedate=2017-04-10}}</ref> Jones then began lobbying the legislatures in multiple states to change laws which place caps on interest, which led to the passage of multiple acts including the Tennessee Deferred Presentment Services Act by the [[Tennessee General Assembly]], which permits payday lending with some restrictions.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news|last=Hendren|first=John|date=January 24, 1999|title=Exorbitant 'Payday Loans' Tide Over the Desperate, Line Lenders' Pockets|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/jan/24/local/me-1145|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|location=Los Angeles|access-date=2019-03-03}}</ref> This act considers the fee to borrow money from a payday lender not to be interest, stating \"the fee, when made and collected, shall not be deemed interest for any purpose of law.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://advance.lexis.com/documentpage/?pdmfid=1000516&crid=fc8945e9-47fd-4e89-b00e-81af3aa1b4e5&nodeid=ABTAARAAM&nodepath=%2FROOT%2FABT%2FABTAAR%2FABTAARAAM&level=3&haschildren=&populated=false&title=45-17-112.+Retention+of+records+--+Operating+costs+--+Deferred+presentment+procedures.&config=025054JABlOTJjNmIyNi0wYjI0LTRjZGEtYWE5ZC0zNGFhOWNhMjFlNDgKAFBvZENhdGFsb2cDFQ14bX2GfyBTaI9WcPX5&pddocfullpath=%2Fshared%2Fdocument%2Fstatutes-legislation%2Furn%3AcontentItem%3A4X8K-TXK0-R03K-4155-00008-00&ecomp=h3t7kkk&prid=2b6533eb-4139-46fd-a0d1-8f877e68d82d|title=Tennessee Code Annotated|last=|first=|date=2011|website=advance.lexis.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nJones' first marriage was to Candace Robinson on November 25, 1972. The couple had a daughter, Courtney Elaine Jones, born in 1973. The marriage ended in 1975. On May 14, 1983, Jones married Paula \"Janie\" Pangle (born 1961) in Bradley County. They have three children: Abby (born 1984), Will (born 1988) and Bailey (born 1991).<ref>{{cite web |title=Allan Jones Challenge Gift for Intercollegiate Aquatic Center Announced |publisher=University of Tennessee |url=http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-swim/spec-rel/110902aaa.html |date=November 9, 2002 |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref><ref name=gen>{{cite web |first=Michael T. |last=Slaughter |title=Michael T. Slaughter Genealogy |url=http://mtsfamily.com/GEDGEN/grpf4074.html |accessdate=August 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812042405/http://www.mtsfamily.com/GEDGEN/grpf4074.html |archivedate=August 12, 2014 |df=mdy-all |url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140811214930/http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-swim/spec-rel/110902aaa.html|archivedate=2014-08-11}}</ref>\n\nJones' residence is called Creekridge and is located on 400 acres north of Cleveland.<ref name=times/> It consists of a more than $5 million house constructed between 2003 and 2009, as well as a football field, horse stables, a greenhouse and a classic car collection.<ref name=msnbc/> It is located near the residence of fellow businessman [[Forrest Preston]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Green|first1=Alex|title=How Forrest Preston built Life Care Centers into the biggest privately held company in the industry|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/business/aroundregion/story/2015/apr/27/how-forrest-preston-built-life-care-centers-biggest-privately-held-company-industry/301066/|accessdate=September 13, 2015|work=timesfreepress|date=April 27, 2015}}</ref> Jones previously lived in the [[Centenary Avenue Historic District]] in downtown Cleveland.<ref name=\"site3\"/>\n\nPolitically, Jones has been an [[Independent (politics)|Independent]], and has donated to the campaigns of both [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politicians, but his views are characterized to be [[Right-wing politics|right-leaning]] and fiscally [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]]. Jones supported [[Donald Trump]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 U.S. Presidential Election]]. A few days after the [[inauguration of President Trump]], Jones stated in an interview with [[Fox & Friends]] that he was \"tired of Presidents who were politicians\" and believed that small businesses would benefit from Trump's policies.<ref>{{cite AV media |people= |date=January 30, 2017|title=Allan Jones on Fox and Friends|trans-title= |medium= |language= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KnkntifOTGQ&t=11s|access-date= |format= |time= |location= |publisher=Fox News|id= |isbn= |oclc= |quote= |ref= }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Toby McKenzie]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://wallanjones.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Allan}}\n[[Category:American chief executives of financial services companies]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Cleveland, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessman}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name = Allan Jones\n| image = Photo of Allan Jones.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = December 31, 1952\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = \n| nationality =\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education = [[Cleveland High School (Tennessee)|Cleveland High School]]\n| alma mater = [[Middle Tennessee State University]]\n| employer = \n| occupation = Businessman\n| title =\n| salary = \n| networth = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party =\n| boards = \n| religion =\n| spouse = Candy Robinson (1972-75)<br/>Janie Pangle (m. 1983)\n| children = 4\n| relatives = \n}}\n'''William Allan Jones Jr.''' (born December 31, 1952) is an American businessman from [[Cleveland, Tennessee]].  He is the founder, chairman, and CEO of [[Check Into Cash]], Creditcorp, Jones Management Services, and the Community Financial Services Association, as well as several other local [[loan|lending agencies]].<ref name=woop>{{cite news|last=Pendergrass|first=Toby|date=April 1, 2011|title=WOOP Investigates The Truth about Allan Jones|url=http://www.woopfm.com/a_jones_Story.htm|work=[[WOOP-FM]]|location=Cleveland, Tennessee|access-date=October 24, 2011}}</ref><ref name=BBB>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbb.org/us/tn/memphis/profile/consumer-finance-companies/check-into-cash-0543-33007054|title=Check Into Cash &#124; Better Business Bureau\u00ae Profile|website=www.bbb.org}}</ref><ref name=JMS>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jonesmanagement.com/welcome.htm |title=Jones Management Services |access-date=June 6, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316051721/http://www.jonesmanagement.com/welcome.htm |archive-date=March 16, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He has been called the \"father of the payday loan industry\" for founding and building the first major [[payday loan]] chain.<ref name=harpers>{{cite web|url=http://harpers.org/archive/2009/04/usury-country/|title=Usury Country &#124; Harper&#039;s Magazine|publisher=harpers.org|accessdate=March 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nJones was born on December 31, 1952, in Cleveland, Tennessee to William A. (Bill) Jones (1919\u20131981) and Virginia Slaughter Jones (1925\u20132003).<ref name=gen/>\n\nJones attended [[Cleveland High School (Tennessee)|Cleveland High School]], where he wrestled and won various awards and served as team captain.<ref name=woop /> He graduated in 1972. Jones credited wrestling with helping build character: \"In wrestling, I didn't have anyone to rely on but me.\" He declined wrestling scholarships to pursue a business degree at [[Middle Tennessee State University]].<ref name=matt>''The Mat''. \"Allan Jones Donates $1 Million to Build Wrestling Facilities\" by Sandra Rowland, May 23, 2001</ref>\n\n== Business career ==\n===Early career===\nJones left college at age 20 to help his father stabilize the family's small business, the Credit Bureau of Cleveland.<ref name=timesfp>Chattanooga Times Free Press, February 24, 2008</ref> He purchased this reporting and debt collection business in 1977 and developed it to become one of the largest credit bureau databases in the state.<ref name=cash />\n\nJones sold the credit reporting side of the business to [[Equifax]] in 1988, although he retained the name and the company's collection agency division. He then built the company to be the largest in Tennessee with offices from Memphis to Atlanta. Jones sold the company in 1998.<ref name=power />\n\nJones founded Check Into Cash in 1993. The idea arose from him seeing a former credit bureau manager who was operating out of a small service station and cashing checks with the agreement that the owner would hold the checks until the next payday before submitting them to the bank. Check Into Cash eventually grew to include 1,300 stores nationwide.<ref name=woop />\n\n=== Check Into Cash ===\n[[File:Check Into Cash store.jpg|thumb|Check Into Cash store.]]\nJones' research revealed the market for small, short term, fee-based loans collateralized by the customer's signature, leading him to found Check Into Cash in 1993.<ref name=cash /> The business model was made possible after Jones allegedly donated large amounts of money to multiple state legislators in order to convince them to change laws that previously prohibited charging of what some have characterized as [[predatory lending|exorbitant interest rate]]s.<ref name=latimes/> In effect, Jones' critics charged that he bought the State legislation that allows him to do business.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brook|first=Daniel|title=Usury country: Welcome to the birthplace of payday lending|journal=Harper's Magazine|date=April 2009|url=http://harpers.org/archive/2009/04/0082451|accessdate=January 7, 2012}}</ref> {{As of|2005}} Check Into Cash was the second largest [[payday loan]] company in the US and was planning to expand on its existing 1,300 locations.<ref name=cash />\n\n=== Community Financial Services Association ===\nJones has been credited with founding the [[Community Financial Services Association of America]], or CFSA in 1999.<ref name=woop /> CFSA is the national trade association for companies that offer small-dollar, short-term loans or payday advances. Through a code of \"Best Practices,\" CFSA members pledge to abide by responsible industry practices that ensure customers understand the cost and risk of short-term payday advances to facilitate the best financial decisions. The practices also require that members hold themselves \"to the highest standard of service\".<ref name=cfsa>[http://cfsaa.com/about-cfsa.aspx \"About CFSA\"], Community Financial Services Association of America</ref>\n\nJones said he founded CFSA after breaking away from the National Check Cashers Association, due to concerns that the NCCA, now called Financial Service Centers of America, was not giving enough attention to the payday lending industry.<ref name=woop />\n\n=== Hardwick Clothes ===\n[[File:Photo of C L Hardwick.jpg|thumb|150px|C.L. Hardwick, founder of Hardwick Clothes]]\n\nIn 2014, Jones purchased [[Hardwick Clothes]], a company founded in Cleveland, in 1880. Hardwick Clothes is the oldest manufacturer of tailor-made clothing in the United States.<ref name=hardwicksale>{{cite news|title=Sewing up the deal |newspaper=Cleveland Banner |date=June 20, 2014 |url=http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/25322373/article-Sewing-up-the-deal |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718181706/http://clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/25322373/article-Sewing-up-the-deal |archivedate=July 18, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nHardwick Clothes, which began as Cleveland Woolen Mills, was one of two companies founded by C.L. Hardwick in the 19th century. Hardwick put his son Joseph in charge of Hardwick Stove, the family's other business, while his son George ran the clothing company. Cleveland Woolen Mills soon evolved into a manufacturing plant, making suits and other items of apparel.<ref name=hardwickhistory>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Fletcher|title=A history of our supplier, Hardwick Clothes|url=http://seersuckerandtweeds.net/2011/06/14/127/|accessdate=July 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812153111/http://seersuckerandtweeds.net/2011/06/14/127/|archive-date=August 12, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Hardwick Stove was absorbed into [[Maytag]] in 1981.\n\nThe company, known for its \"Sewn in the South\" slogan and renowned during the 1960s for making the world's best blazer, was facing bankruptcy when Jones acquired it. Jones has said he was attracted to Hardwick Clothes because it was the oldest business of its kind in America, and is convinced that the American consumer pendulum is swinging back to \"made in America.\"<ref name=hardwickhistory />\n\nWithin weeks of purchasing Hardwick Clothes, Jones named Bruce Bellusci, former executive vice president at Hart Schafner & Marx, the company's new CEO/president.<ref name=brucebellusci>{{cite news|title=Bruce Bellusci Is New President Of Hardwick Clothes|newspaper=The Chattanoogan|date=July 23, 2014|url=http://www.chattanoogan.com/2014/7/23/280948/Bruce-Bellusci-Is-New-President-Of.aspx}}</ref> He also recruited Hart's designer, engineer, and three top salesmen to Hardwick.\n\nIn September 2017, Jones made national headlines when he announced that Hardwick Clothes, Check Into Cash and his other companies would no longer advertise during NFL games as a response to the [[U.S. national anthem protests (2016\u2013present)|national anthem protests]] by the league's players, which the businessman called \"unpatriotic behavior.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=September 27, 2017 |title=Cleveland Businessman Allan Jones Pulls NFL Ads After National Anthem Snub |url=http://www.chattanoogan.com/2017/9/27/355672/Cleveland-Businessman-Allan-Jones-Pulls.aspx |work=Chattanoogan |location= |access-date=November 3, 2017 }}</ref> Jones was featured on the [[Fox Business Network]] discussing the decision.<ref>{{cite AV media |people= |date=September 29, 2017|title=Tennessee business owner on pulling ads from NFL|trans-title= |medium= |language= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cfR3p4GHWPI|access-date=November 19, 2017|format=Video|time= |location= |publisher=Fox Business |id= |isbn= |oclc= |quote= |ref=}}</ref>\n\nJones sold Hardwick in December 2019 to the company Puerto Rico Industries for the Blind.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesfreepress.com/news/business/aroundregion/story/2019/dec/16/americas-oldest-suit-maker-hnew-ownerpuerrico/510722/|title=Hardwick Clothes in Cleveland acquired by Puerto Rico nonprofit, will add 100 workers|website=timesfreepress.com|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\n===Other business ventures===\nJones is the largest property owner in [[Bradley County, Tennessee|Bradley County]] and has renovated many buildings, including a former shopping mall that he altered to become a site for his companies.<ref name=woop />\n\nThe Cleveland/Bradley Chamber of Commerce awarded Jones with the M.C. Headrick Free Enterprise Award, the organization's highest honor in 2003.<ref name=woop /> That same year Jones was inducted into the [[University of Tennessee at Chattanooga]]\u2019s Entrepreneurship Hall of Fame.<ref name=utc>[http://www.utc.edu/Academic/HarrisChair/2003.php \"Entrepreneurship Hall of Fame, 2003\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110308065748/http://www.utc.edu/Academic/HarrisChair/2003.php |date=March 8, 2011 }}, October 2003.</ref>\n\nJones was included on ''BusinessTN'' magazine's \"Power 100\" list in 2005.<ref name=power>''BusinessTN'', July 2005.</ref> Jones appeared on the cover of ''BusinessTN'' Magazine and was characterized as \"The King of Cash\". The magazine ranked Jones as one of the 20 wealthiest people in Tennessee.<ref name=cash>Drew Ruble, [http://businesstn.com/content/king-cash \"The King of Cash\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110825202735/http://businesstn.com/content/king-cash |date=August 25, 2011 }}, ''BusinessTN'', July 2005</ref>\n\nIn addition to Check Into Cash, Jones has founded or purchased several affiliate agencies, including U.S. Money Shops, a [[Pawnbroker|pawn agency]], LendingFrog.com, an online lending agency, Loan By Phone, and Buy Here Pay Here USA, a [[used car]] [[car loan|finance dealer]].<ref name=times>{{cite news |last=Green|first=Alex |date=February 5, 2015 |title=The Lord of Loans: How Cleveland payday-loan pioneer Allan Jones was propelled to fame and fortune |url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/business/aroundregion/story/2015/feb/05/lord-loans-how-clevelands-payday-loan-pioneer-allan-jones-was-propelled-fame-and-fortune/286693/|work=[[Chattanooga Times Free Press]] |location= |access-date=November 3, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n== High school wrestling support ==\n[[File:Jones_Wrestling_Center.jpg|thumb|200px|Jones Wrestling Center]]\n[[File:Allan jones wrestling.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Jones, far left, inside the Jones Wrestling Center.]]\n\nJones is the largest individual supporter of high school wrestling in the United States.{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}} He founded the Cleveland/Bradley Wrestling Club in 1990,<ref name=autogenerated1>''The Mat'', \"Allan Jones Donates A Million Dollars\", by Sandra Rowland, May 23, 2001.</ref> and provided the $1.3 million funding for the Jones Wrestling Center located on the Cleveland High School campus.<ref name=\"woop\"/> The clubs have been successful, with Jones remarking that \u201cIt has very little to do with the buildings and it has everything to do with the right coaches.\u201d<ref name=\"woop\"/>\n\nIn the 2013 state championship, Cleveland beat runner-up Wilson Central 78-4, setting a TSSAA record for the most lopsided margin of victory, most pins and quickest championship. Since the 2006-07 season, the wrestling team has won state championships in 2011, 2013 and 2014, 2015, and 2018.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Cleveland Daily Banner |title=Wrestling center gets funding for addition |url=http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/24750591/article-Wrestling-center-gets-funding-for-addition |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129075249/http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/24750591/article-Wrestling-center-gets-funding-for-addition |archivedate=November 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Jones received national attention when he auctioned off a 2009 King Ranch [[F-150]] four-wheel drive pickup truck autographed twice by President [[George W. Bush]]. The proceeds of the auction went to benefit Cleveland's Higher Calling Youth Wrestling Club and the National Wrestling Hall of Fame Dan Gable Museum. \n<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Cleveland Daily Banner |title=Jones puts Bush\u2019s truck on auction block |url=http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/jones-puts-bushs-truck-on-auction-block,55603  }}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropy ==\n[[File:Allan Jones Aquatic Center.jpg|thumb|Allan Jones Aquatic Center]]\n\nJones has been described as \"Cleveland\u2019s most celebrated benefactor.\"<ref name=cash />\n\nIn 1990, Jones founded MainStreet Cleveland, dedicated to the revitalization and promotion of Cleveland's historic downtown area and donated the funds for the construction of the Virgil F. Carmichael addition to the Cleveland Public Library.<ref name=woop /> He also wrote and funded Cleveland's Shade Tree Ordinance that helped the city's tree board earn the designation of Tennessee Tree Board of the Year in 2010.  Many of the trees that line the city's streets were donated by his foundation. He donated $4 million to the [[University of Tennessee]] at Knoxville for construction of a new Allan Jones Aquatic Center.<ref name=cash />\n\nIn 2011, Allan Jones contributed to the non-profit organization [[tnAchieves]], enabling it to launch its scholarship and mentoring program in all three Bradley County high schools, ensuring that every graduating senior from Cleveland High School, [[Walker Valley High School]], and [[Bradley Central High School]] had the opportunity to attend [[Cleveland State Community College]].<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Carroll |title=Cleveland, Bradley Students Get College Tuition Help |publisher=WRCBtv.com |date=August 4, 2011 |url=http://www.wrcbtv.com/story/15212583/cleveland-bradley-students-get-college-tuition-help|accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> In 2015, Jones was awarded the first-ever honorary degree from Cleveland State during its 49th Commencement Ceremony where he was the keynote speaker. A few days later, Jones received the Chancellor's Award for Excellence in Philanthropy from the Tennessee Board of Regents.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cleveland State Honors Allan Jones with Philanthropy Award|url=http://www.clevelandstatecc.edu/news/article/cleveland-state-honors-allan-jones-with-philanthropy-award|website=www.clevelandstateecc.edu|access-date=March 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417070827/http://www.clevelandstatecc.edu/news/article/cleveland-state-honors-allan-jones-with-philanthropy-award|archive-date=April 17, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Jones received the prestigious Fred Gregg Jr. award from the Greater Chattanooga Sports Hall of Fame for significant contributions to sports.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gregg Award going to Jones|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/sports/local/story/2012/feb/12/gregg-award-going-to-jones/70496/|website=www.timesfreepress.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the Jones family gave a donation to Lee University to purchase the old First Baptist Church building in downtown Cleveland and renovate it into a music performance hall. The building was named \u201cPangle Hall\u201d in honor of Jones' wife Janie Pangle Jones. Lee University President [[Paul Conn]] said Pangle Hall was only possible due to this donation.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Lee to dedicate Pangle Hall with student, faculty, alumni music |url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/chattanooganow/music/story/2014/oct/23/lee-dedicate-pangle-hall-student-faculty-alumni-mu/270183/ |work=Times Free Press |location=Chattanooga, Tennessee |date=October 23, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Jones made national headlines after he donated 43,000 pairs of eclipse-viewing sunglasses to students in six Tennessee school systems. The businessman said the donation was made to ensure students who wanted to view the solar eclipse did so only with safe, NASA-approved glasses.\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Protect those eyes! Businessman focused on kids\u2019 safety|url= http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/protect-those-eyes,63715|website=www.clevelandbanner.com}}</ref>\n\n== Tall Betsy ==\n{{main|Tall Betsy}}\n[[File:Photo_of_Tall_Betsy,_Fort_Hill_Cemetery,_1993.jpg|thumb|Photo of Tall Betsy in Fort Hill Cemetery, 1993.]]\nJones is credited with the creation of the legend of [[Tall Betsy]], a [[Halloween]] cultural icon based in Bradley County.\n\nJones based the character on stories (local folklore) that were told to his mother, Virginia Slaughter Jones, by her mother, Marie Schultz Slaughter. Virginia and other Cleveland children being raised during the 1930s were told by their parents that if they failed to come home before dark they would likely encounter Tall Betsy, sometimes called Black Betsy or simply \"The Lady in Black.\"<ref>Woop FM.com, April 1, 2011, \u201cWOOP Investigates the Legend of Tall Betsy\u201d</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Jones' home on [[Centenary Avenue Historic District|Centenary Avenue]] was the site of a Halloween world record. According to media reports, the Jones family handed out 11,201 pieces of bubblegum from 5 pm to 8 pm.<ref name=\"site3\">[http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/tall-betsy-set-to-appearat-block-party-730-pm,21130 Tall Betsy to Appear at Block Party], Cleveland Daily Banner, Official Site. Retrieved October 30, 2015.</ref>\n\nTall Betsy last appeared in 1998 after drawing a Halloween crowd of 25,000, although no explanation was ever given for the goblin's disappearance. Jones later told a reporter that while the goblin may have vanished, her spirit is embedded in the hearts and minds of the Cleveland residents who saw Tall Betsy during the eighteen years from 1980 to 1998.\n\nThe 2005 Block Party was dedicated in honor of Tall Betsy's 25th anniversary. The Block Party drew the largest crowd in the event's history. Jones arranged for nationally recognized celebrities such as the cast of \"Leave It To Beaver\" and Little Richard to entertain the more than 30,000 attendees. The Tennessee legislature declared Tall Betsy the official Halloween goblin of Bradley County in 1989. In 2011 the character was the subject of a documentary film.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Cleveland Daily Banner |title='Tall Betsy' returning to life in documentary |date=October 13, 2011 |url=http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/15846428/article-%E2%80%98Tall-Betsy%E2%80%99-returning-to-life-in-documentary |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121127164633/http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/15846428/article-%E2%80%98Tall-Betsy%E2%80%99-returning-to-life-in-documentary |archivedate=November 27, 2012 |accessdate=August 12, 2015}}</ref> In 2014, Jones\u2019 son, Bailey, assumed the identity of Tall Betsy and has appeared as the goblin each year at Halloween.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tall Betsy Set to Appear at Block Party|url=http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/tall-betsy-set-to-appearat-block-party-730-pm,21130|website=clevelandbanner.com}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism and controversy ==\n\nJones\u2019 company Check Into Cash has received criticism for its high interest rates and for harming its customers. Most believe that payday loans target those of low-income.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bestcompany.com/payday-loans/company/check-into-cash|title=Check Into Cash Reviews - Real Customer Reviews|work=Best Company|access-date=January 15, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nThe April 28, 2010, episode of [[MSNBC]]'s ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show]]'', had a segment about the payday loan industry. Maddow criticized Jones for charging people high interest rates.<ref name=\"msnbc\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.com/transcripts/rachel-maddow-show/2010-04-28|title=The Rachel Maddow Show, Transcript 04/28/10|work=MSNBC|access-date=October 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2010 interview with ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', when asked about the lack of diversity in his hometown of Cleveland, Jones allegedly said, \u201cWe have just enough blacks to put together a decent basketball team \u2014 but not so many the good people of Cleveland, Tennessee need to worry about crime. That\u2019s why I can leave my keys in the car with the door unlocked\u201d.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/gary-rivlin/portrait-of-a-subprime-le_b_602182.html|title=Portrait of a Subprime Lender: Allan Jones, Payday King|last=Rivlin|first=Gary|date=June 6, 2010|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> He noted that many of his company managers and friends are African Americans. The article cited an anonymous source who claimed some company employees referred to a black man who shines shoes as the \"Little Chocolate Man\u201d although no source for the comment was ever provided.<ref name=\":1\" /> Also in that interview, a former employee of Jones' company stated that Jones\u2019 barber shop was successful because of \u201cfemale barbers with big titties.\u201d<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/news/story/2010/jun/21/check-into-cash-founder-jones-denies-racial/20871/|title=Check into Cash founder Jones denies racial remarks|last=Report|first=Staff|date=June 21, 2010|website=Times Free Press|language=en-US|access-date=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJones denied ever making the statements to numerous media outlets and claimed he was misquoted, stating \"I gave generously of my time\u2026to assist in the preparation for writing a book, purported to fairly represent the credit needs of the middle income working population and the markets that serve them. Unfortunately, (the author) has chosen to rearrange some of my remarks to draw incorrect conclusions regarding my personal views and beliefs.\"<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n===Legal issues===\nJones was indicted on federal charges of [[wiretapping]] in 1975 after he placed a recording device on his first wife's telephone in October 1974 after she had been granted a [[restraining order]] against him, allegedly to determine if she was having an extramarital affair, which she reportedly was. Jones reportedly used information from the recordings to obtain a divorce. His indictment was dismissed by the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Tennessee|local district court]] before Jones could go to trial, and this dismissal was subsequently upheld by the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]] in 1976.<ref>{{cite court|litigants=United States of America, Plaintiff-Appellant, v. William Allan Jones Jr., Defendant-Appellee.|vol=542|reporter=F.2d|opinion=661|pinpoint=|court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]]|date=1976|url=https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/339314/united-states-v-william-allan-jones/|accessdate=2019-03-03|quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe legality of Jones' payday loan model was challenged shortly after Check into Cash was founded.<ref name=checkhistory>{{cite news|last=Bowers|first=Larry C.|date=July 12, 2018|title=Jones reflects on \u2018Check\u2019 history\n|url=http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/allan-jones-interview,83354|work=Cleveland Daily Banner|location=Cleveland, Tennessee|access-date=2019-03-03}}</ref> Initially Jones and other payday lenders claimed that the fee charged did not constitute interest, and therefore did not violate laws capping a maximum interest on loans, which runs contrary to multiple federal laws.<ref name=latimes/> In 1997 Check Into Cash was sued in a [[class-action lawsuit]] by two Cleveland attorneys, representing multiple customers, alleging violation of the [[Truth in Lending Act]] and [[Fair Debt Collection Act]], as well as other illegal practices. Check Into Cash eventually settled the case by paying $2.2 million to the class and $500,000 in attorneys' fees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.in.gov/dfi/2366.htm|title=The Growth of Legal Loan Sharking: A Report on the Payday Loan Industry|last=Fox|first=Jean Ann|date=November 1998|website=in.gov|publisher=Consumer Federation of America|access-date=2019-03-03|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20170410211246/https://www.in.gov/dfi/2366.htm|archivedate=2017-04-10}}</ref> Jones then began lobbying the legislatures in multiple states to change laws which place caps on interest, which led to the passage of multiple acts including the Tennessee Deferred Presentment Services Act by the [[Tennessee General Assembly]], which permits payday lending with some restrictions.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news|last=Hendren|first=John|date=January 24, 1999|title=Exorbitant 'Payday Loans' Tide Over the Desperate, Line Lenders' Pockets|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/jan/24/local/me-1145|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|location=Los Angeles|access-date=2019-03-03}}</ref> This act considers the fee to borrow money from a payday lender not to be interest, stating \"the fee, when made and collected, shall not be deemed interest for any purpose of law.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://advance.lexis.com/documentpage/?pdmfid=1000516&crid=fc8945e9-47fd-4e89-b00e-81af3aa1b4e5&nodeid=ABTAARAAM&nodepath=%2FROOT%2FABT%2FABTAAR%2FABTAARAAM&level=3&haschildren=&populated=false&title=45-17-112.+Retention+of+records+--+Operating+costs+--+Deferred+presentment+procedures.&config=025054JABlOTJjNmIyNi0wYjI0LTRjZGEtYWE5ZC0zNGFhOWNhMjFlNDgKAFBvZENhdGFsb2cDFQ14bX2GfyBTaI9WcPX5&pddocfullpath=%2Fshared%2Fdocument%2Fstatutes-legislation%2Furn%3AcontentItem%3A4X8K-TXK0-R03K-4155-00008-00&ecomp=h3t7kkk&prid=2b6533eb-4139-46fd-a0d1-8f877e68d82d|title=Tennessee Code Annotated|last=|first=|date=2011|website=advance.lexis.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nJones' first marriage was to Candace Robinson on November 25, 1972. The couple had a daughter, Courtney Elaine Jones, born in 1973. The marriage ended in 1975. On May 14, 1983, Jones married Paula \"Janie\" Pangle (born 1961) in Bradley County. They have three children: Abby (born 1984), Will (born 1988) and Bailey (born 1991).<ref>{{cite web |title=Allan Jones Challenge Gift for Intercollegiate Aquatic Center Announced |publisher=University of Tennessee |url=http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-swim/spec-rel/110902aaa.html |date=November 9, 2002 |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref><ref name=gen>{{cite web |first=Michael T. |last=Slaughter |title=Michael T. Slaughter Genealogy |url=http://mtsfamily.com/GEDGEN/grpf4074.html |accessdate=August 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812042405/http://www.mtsfamily.com/GEDGEN/grpf4074.html |archivedate=August 12, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nJones' residence is called Creekridge and is located on 400 acres north of Cleveland.<ref name=times/> It consists of a more than $5 million house constructed between 2003 and 2009, as well as a football field, horse stables, a greenhouse and a classic car collection.<ref name=msnbc/> It is located near the residence of fellow businessman [[Forrest Preston]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Green|first1=Alex|title=How Forrest Preston built Life Care Centers into the biggest privately held company in the industry|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/business/aroundregion/story/2015/apr/27/how-forrest-preston-built-life-care-centers-biggest-privately-held-company-industry/301066/|accessdate=September 13, 2015|work=timesfreepress|date=April 27, 2015}}</ref> Jones previously lived in the [[Centenary Avenue Historic District]] in downtown Cleveland.<ref name=\"site3\"/>\n\nPolitically, Jones has been an [[Independent (politics)|Independent]], and has donated to the campaigns of both [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politicians, but his views are characterized to be [[Right-wing politics|right-leaning]] and fiscally [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]]. Jones supported [[Donald Trump]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 U.S. Presidential Election]]. A few days after the [[inauguration of President Trump]], Jones stated in an interview with [[Fox & Friends]] that he was \"tired of Presidents who were politicians\" and believed that small businesses would benefit from Trump's policies.<ref>{{cite AV media |people= |date=January 30, 2017|title=Allan Jones on Fox and Friends|trans-title= |medium= |language= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KnkntifOTGQ&t=11s|access-date= |format= |time= |location= |publisher=Fox News|id= |isbn= |oclc= |quote= |ref= }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Toby McKenzie]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://wallanjones.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Allan}}\n[[Category:American chief executives of financial services companies]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Cleveland, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n", "name_user": "Bneu2013", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:archive dead url", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allan_Jones_(businessman)"}
{"title_page": "Laodicea in Syria", "text_new": "{{coord|35.51892275|N|35.7766297|E|display=title}}\n[[File:LatakiaArco.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Laodicea's \"Tetraporticus\", built by [[Septimius Severus]] in AD 193]]\n\n'''Laodicea''' ({{lang-grc|\u039b\u03b1\u03bf\u03b4\u03af\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1}}) was a [[port city]] and an important [[Colonia (Roman)|colonia]] of the [[Roman Empire]] in ancient [[Syria]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z_IBAwAAQBAJ|title=Monuments of Syria: A Guide|first=Ross|last=Burns|date=30 June 2009|publisher=I.B.Tauris|accessdate=11 June 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref> located near the modern city of [[Latakia]]. It was also called '''Laodicea in Syria''' or '''Laodicea ad mare'''. For a short period of time under [[Septimius Severus]], it became the capital of [[Roman Syria]], and subsequently, it became the capital of the [[Theodorias (province)|Eastern Roman province of Theodorias]] from 528 AD until 637 AD.\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Bakhos temple latakia.jpg|thumb|upright|200px|Temple of [[Dionysus|Bacchus]] in actual Latakia]]\n[[File:Heinrich Kiepert. Asia citerior.Coele.Syria.jpg|thumb|left|350px| Map showing Laodicea during Roman times]]\nThe [[Phoenicia]]n city of [[Ramitha]] was located in the coastal area where it is the modern port of Latakia, known to the Greeks as Leuk\u00ea Akt\u00ea or \"white coast\". Laodicea got its name when was first founded in the fourth century BC under the rule of the [[Seleucid Empire]]: it was named by [[Seleucus I Nicator]] in honor of his mother, [[Laodice of Macedonia|Laodice]] ({{Lang-el|\u039b\u03b1\u03bf\u03b4\u03af\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u1f21 \u03a0\u03ac\u03c1\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2}}). The city was subsequently ruled by the [[Roman Empire|Romans]] until the Arab conquest in 637 AD.\n\nThe Roman [[Pompey the Great]] conquered the city from the Armenian king [[Tigranes the Great]] alongside with all of Syria in 64 BCE and later [[Julius Caesar]] declared the city \"free polis\". During the [[Severan dynasty]], a third century imperial dynasty of Rome from Syrian origins, the emperor [[Septimius Severus]] named with the title \"Metropolis\" the city in 194 AD and allowed the ''Ius Italicum'' (exemption from empire taxation) to Laodicea, that was later called a \"Roman Colonia\". Some Roman merchants moved to live in the city under [[Augustus]], but the city was always culturally \"greek\" influenced. The Romans made a \"Pharum\" at the port, that was renowned as one of the best of Ancient Levant; then created a [[Roman road]] from southern [[Anatolia]] toward [[Berytus]] and [[Damascus]], that greatly improved the commerce through the port of Laodicea.\n\n{{Quote|There are few remains of what was a rich and well-built town (Strab. 16.2.9): colonnades, a monumental arch, sarcophagi, all within the modern town. The sanctuaries, public baths, amphitheater, hippodrome, mentioned by ancient authors or by Greek inscriptions, and the rampart gates depicted on coins, have all disappeared...The town occupies a rocky promontory...Including the port, its area was ca. 220 ha...A wide avenue, bordered with porticos in Roman times, ran N-S across the town, from the tip of the peninsula to the gate where the road to Antioch started; perpendicular to this, three colonnaded streets ran from E to W. The one to the N was centered on the entry to the citadel on the high hill to the NE. The central one came from the E gate, where the Apamea road reached the city. The street today is occupied by the great souk, where there is still an alignment of 13 monolithic granite columns. A tetrapylon marked the crossing of this thoroughfare with the N-S avenue. The S street began at the port and ended to the E at the long steep hill to the SE, where a monumental four-way arch, erroneously called a tetrapylon, closed off the view. This arch consists of four semicircular arches, one on each side, supporting a stone cupola. Columns engaged in pilasters serve as buttresses at the corners of the four masonry moles. Not far away, inside a mosque, is the corner of a Corinthian peristyle, with capitals and entablature. Virtually nothing remains of the theater, which was built against the SE hill and whose cavea had a diameter of ca. 100 m. Princeton: ''Laodicea ad mare''}}\n\nThe city enjoyed a huge economic prosperity thanks to the wine produced in the hills around the port and exported to all the empire. The city was famous because of the textile products.{{Citation needed|date=August 2017}} Laodicea minted coins from an early Roman date, but the most famous are from [[Septimius Severus|Severian]] times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forumancientcoins.com/dougsmith/feac62mac.html|title=Featured Coin|publisher=|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:At the National Museum in Lattakia.jpg|thumb|right|Classical Statue at the National Museum of Latakia]]\nA sizable [[Jewish people|Jewish]] population lived in Laodicea during the first century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/9631-laodicea|title=LAODICEA - JewishEncyclopedia.com|publisher=|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref>   Under [[Septimius Severus]] the city was fortified and was made for a few years the capital of Roman Syria: in this period Laodicea grew to be a city of nearly 40000 inhabitants and had even an hippodrome.\n\nChristianity was the main religion in the city after [[Constantine I]] and there were many bishops of Laodicea who participated in ecumenical councils, mainly during Byzantine times. The heretic [[Apollinaris of Laodicea|Apollinarius]] was [[bishop]] of Laodicea in the 4th century, when the city was fully [[Christianity|Christian]] but with a few remaining Jews.\n\nAn earthquake damaged the city in 494 AD<ref name=watson1996>{{Citation|title=International Dictionary of Historic Places|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/?id=R44VRnNCzAYC&pg=RA1-PA451 |chapter=Latakia |editor=Noelle Watson |publisher=Fitzroy Dearborn |year=1996|isbn=9781884964039}}</ref> and successively [[Justinian I]] made Laodicea the capital of the Byzantine province of \"[[Theodorias (province)|Theodorias]]\" in the early sixth century. Laodicea remained its capital for more than a century until the Arab conquest.\n\n==Bishops of Laodicea==\n\nThe same [[Saint Paul]] visited Laodicea and made the first Christians in the city. Slowly the bishops of Laodicea grew in importance but were always under the [[Patriarch of Antioch]]. The most important bishops were:\n\n* ''San'' [[Lucius of Cyrene]] \u2020\n* Telimidres \u2020 (in 250/260 AD)\n* Eliodorus \u2020\n* Socrates \u2020\n* Eusebius \u2020 (around 276 AD)\n* Anatolius \u2020 (in 280 AD)\n* Stefanus \u2020 (under [[Diocletianus]])\n** Teodotus \u2020 (325 - 335 AD) (bishop [[Arianism|arian]])\n** [[George of Laodicea|Giorgius]] \u2020 (335 - 363 AD) (bishop [[Arianism|arian]])\n* ''San'' Pelagius \u2020 (363 - 381 AD)\n* [[Apollinaris of Laodicea|Apollinarius]] (died 390 AD). He collaborated with his father [[Apollinaris (the Elder)|Apollinaris the Elder]] in reproducing the [[Old Testament]] in the form of [[Homer]]ic and [[Pindar]]ic poetry, and the [[New Testament]] after the fashion of [[Plato]]nic [[dialogue]]s, when the emperor [[Julian the Apostate|Julian]] had forbidden Christians to teach the [[classics]].\n* Elpidius \u2020 (around 400 AD)\n* Macarius \u2020 (429-451 AD)\n* Maximus \u2020 (around 458 AD)\n* Nicia \u2020\n* Costantinus \u2020 (510 - 518 AD)\n* Stephanus \u2020 (553 AD)\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n* Butcher, Kevin. ''Roman Syria and the Near East'' Getty Publications. Los Angeles, 2003 {{ISBN|0892367156}} ([https://books.google.com/books?id=YJPn3-rRjC0C&pg=PA230&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=3#v=onepage&q&f=false])\n* Ross Burns. ''Monuments of Syria: A Guide''. Publisher I.B.Tauris. New York, 2009  {{ISBN|0857714899}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Berytus]]\n* [[Theodorias (province)]]\n* [[Apollinaris of Laodicea]]\n* [[Antioch]]\n\n{{Roman colonies in ancient Levant}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 4th century BC]]\n[[Category:Populated places disestablished in the 7th century]]\n[[Category:Seleucid colonies]]\n[[Category:Coloniae (Roman)]]\n[[Category:Roman sites in Syria]]\n[[Category:Populated places of the Byzantine Empire]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Latakia Governorate]]\n[[Category:Latakia]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|35.51892275|N|35.7766297|E|display=title}}\n[[File:LatakiaArco.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Laodicea's \"Tetraporticus\", built by [[Septimius Severus]] in AD 193]]\n\n'''Laodicea''' ({{lang-grc|\u039b\u03b1\u03bf\u03b4\u03af\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1}}) was a [[port city]] and an important [[Colonia (Roman)|colonia]] of the [[Roman Empire]] in ancient [[Syria]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z_IBAwAAQBAJ|title=Monuments of Syria: A Guide|first=Ross|last=Burns|date=30 June 2009|publisher=I.B.Tauris|accessdate=11 June 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref> located near the modern city of [[Latakia]]. It was also called '''Laodicea in Syria''' or '''Laodicea ad mare'''. For a short period of time under [[Septimius Severus]], it became the capital of [[Roman Syria]], and subsequently, it became the capital of the [[Theodorias (province)|Eastern Roman province of Theodorias]] from 528 AD until 637 AD.\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Bakhos temple latakia.jpg|thumb|upright|200px|Temple of [[Dionysus|Bacchus]] in actual Latakia]]\n[[File:Heinrich Kiepert. Asia citerior.Coele.Syria.jpg|thumb|left|350px| Map showing Laodicea during Roman times]]\nThe [[Phoenicia]]n city of [[Ramitha]] was located in the coastal area where it is the modern port of Latakia, known to the Greeks as Leuk\u00ea Akt\u00ea or \"white coast\". Laodicea got its name when was first founded in the fourth century BC under the rule of the [[Seleucid Empire]]: it was named by [[Seleucus I Nicator]] in honor of his mother, [[Laodice of Macedonia|Laodice]] ({{Lang-el|\u039b\u03b1\u03bf\u03b4\u03af\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u1f21 \u03a0\u03ac\u03c1\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2}}). The city was subsequently ruled by the [[Roman Empire|Romans]] until the Arab conquest in 637 AD.\n\nThe Roman [[Pompey the Great]] conquered the city from the Armenian king [[Tigranes the Great]] alongside with all of Syria in 64 BCE and later [[Julius Caesar]] declared the city \"free polis\". During the [[Severan dynasty]], a third century imperial dynasty of Rome from Syrian origins, the emperor [[Septimius Severus]] named with the title \"Metropolis\" the city in 194 AD and allowed the ''Ius Italicum'' (exemption from empire taxation) to Laodicea, that was later called a \"Roman Colonia\". Some Roman merchants moved to live in the city under [[Augustus]], but the city was always culturally \"greek\" influenced. The Romans made a \"Pharum\" at the port, that was renowned as one of the best of Ancient Levant; then created a [[Roman road]] from southern [[Anatolia]] toward [[Berytus]] and [[Damascus]], that greatly improved the commerce through the port of Laodicea.\n\n{{Quote|There are few remains of what was a rich and well-built town (Strab. 16.2.9): colonnades, a monumental arch, sarcophagi, all within the modern town. The sanctuaries, public baths, amphitheater, hippodrome, mentioned by ancient authors or by Greek inscriptions, and the rampart gates depicted on coins, have all disappeared...The town occupies a rocky promontory...Including the port, its area was ca. 220 ha...A wide avenue, bordered with porticos in Roman times, ran N-S across the town, from the tip of the peninsula to the gate where the road to Antioch started; perpendicular to this, three colonnaded streets ran from E to W. The one to the N was centered on the entry to the citadel on the high hill to the NE. The central one came from the E gate, where the Apamea road reached the city. The street today is occupied by the great souk, where there is still an alignment of 13 monolithic granite columns. A tetrapylon marked the crossing of this thoroughfare with the N-S avenue. The S street began at the port and ended to the E at the long steep hill to the SE, where a monumental four-way arch, erroneously called a tetrapylon, closed off the view. This arch consists of four semicircular arches, one on each side, supporting a stone cupola. Columns engaged in pilasters serve as buttresses at the corners of the four masonry moles. Not far away, inside a mosque, is the corner of a Corinthian peristyle, with capitals and entablature. Virtually nothing remains of the theater, which was built against the SE hill and whose cavea had a diameter of ca. 100 m. Princeton: ''Laodicea ad mare''}}\n\nThe city enjoyed a huge economic prosperity thanks to the wine produced in the hills around the port and exported to all the empire. The city was famous because of the textile products.{{Citation needed|date=August 2017}} Laodicea minted coins from an early Roman date, but the most famous are from [[Septimius Severus|Severian]] times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forumancientcoins.com/dougsmith/feac62mac.html|title=Featured Coin|publisher=|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:At the National Museum in Lattakia.jpg|thumb|right|Classical Statue at the National Museum of Latakia]]\nA sizable [[Jewish people|Jewish]] population lived in Laodicea during the first century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/9631-laodicea|title=LAODICEA - JewishEncyclopedia.com|publisher=|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref>   Under [[Septimius Severus]] the city was fortified and was made for a few years the capital of Roman Syria: in this period Laodicea grew to be a city of nearly 40000 inhabitants and had even an hippodrome.\n\nChristianity was the main religion in the city after [[Constantine I]] and there were many bishops of Laodicea who participated in ecumenical councils, mainly during Byzantine times. The heretic [[Apollinaris of Laodicea|Apollinarius]] was [[bishop]] of Laodicea in the 4th century, when the city was fully [[Christianity|Christian]] but with a few remaining Jews.\n\nAn earthquake damaged the city in 494 AD<ref name=watson1996>{{Citation|title=International Dictionary of Historic Places|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/?id=R44VRnNCzAYC&pg=RA1-PA451 |chapter=Latakia |editor=Noelle Watson |publisher=Fitzroy Dearborn |year=1996|isbn=9781884964039}}</ref> and successively [[Justinian I]] made Laodicea the capital of the Byzantine province of \"[[Theodorias (province)|Theodorias]]\" in the early sixth century. Laodicea remained its capital for more than a century until the Arab conquest.\n\n==Bishops of Laodicea==\n\nThe same [[Saint Paul]] visited Laodicea and made the first Christians in the city. Slowly the bishops of Laodicea grew in importance but were always under the [[Patriarch of Antioch]]. The most important bishops were:\n\n* ''San'' [[Lucius of Cyrene]] \u2020\n* Telimidres \u2020 (in 250/260 AD)\n* Eliodorus \u2020\n* Socrates \u2020\n* Eusebius \u2020 (around 276 AD)\n* Anatolius \u2020 (in 280 AD)\n* Stefanus \u2020 (under [[Diocletianus]])\n** Teodotus \u2020 (325 - 335 AD) (bishop [[Arianism|arian]])\n** Giorgius \u2020 (335 - 363 AD) (bishop [[Arianism|arian]])\n* ''San'' Pelagius \u2020 (363 - 381 AD)\n* [[Apollinaris of Laodicea|Apollinarius]] (died 390 AD). He collaborated with his father [[Apollinaris (the Elder)|Apollinaris the Elder]] in reproducing the [[Old Testament]] in the form of [[Homer]]ic and [[Pindar]]ic poetry, and the [[New Testament]] after the fashion of [[Plato]]nic [[dialogue]]s, when the emperor [[Julian the Apostate|Julian]] had forbidden Christians to teach the [[classics]].\n* Elpidius \u2020 (around 400 AD)\n* Macarius \u2020 (429-451 AD)\n* Maximus \u2020 (around 458 AD)\n* Nicia \u2020\n* Costantinus \u2020 (510 - 518 AD)\n* Stephanus \u2020 (553 AD)\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n* Butcher, Kevin. ''Roman Syria and the Near East'' Getty Publications. Los Angeles, 2003 {{ISBN|0892367156}} ([https://books.google.com/books?id=YJPn3-rRjC0C&pg=PA230&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=3#v=onepage&q&f=false])\n* Ross Burns. ''Monuments of Syria: A Guide''. Publisher I.B.Tauris. New York, 2009  {{ISBN|0857714899}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Berytus]]\n* [[Theodorias (province)]]\n* [[Apollinaris of Laodicea]]\n* [[Antioch]]\n\n{{Roman colonies in ancient Levant}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 4th century BC]]\n[[Category:Populated places disestablished in the 7th century]]\n[[Category:Seleucid colonies]]\n[[Category:Coloniae (Roman)]]\n[[Category:Roman sites in Syria]]\n[[Category:Populated places of the Byzantine Empire]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Latakia Governorate]]\n[[Category:Latakia]]\n", "name_user": "Srnec", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBishops of Laodicea:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laodicea_in_Syria"}
{"title_page": "Sparkle 2 Evo", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n| collapsible = \n| state = \n| italic title = \n| title = Sparkle 2 Evo\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| developer = Madman Theory Games<br/>Plastic Games\n| publisher = Forever Entertainment\n| series = \n| engine = \n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[macOS]], [[Linux]], [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| released = November 29, 2011<br/>'''Nintendo Switch''': November 2, 2017\n| genre = Logic, arcade\n| modes = [[Single player]]\n}}\n'''''Sparkle 2 Evo''''' (stylized as '''''The Sparkle\u00b2 evo''''' or '''''Sparkle 2 EVO''''') is a logic-arcade [[video game]]. It is the first title in Forever Entertainment's ''Sparkle'' series of video games and the predecessor of the 2015 video game ''[[Sparkle 3 Genesis]].''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamepressure.com/games/series.asp?ID=3547|title=Sparkle (Forever Entertainment) Video Game Series|website=Gamepressure.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\n''Sparkle 2 Evo'' was developed by Madman Theory Games in collaboration with Plastic Games and published by Forever Entertainment on November 29, 2011 for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[macOS]], and [[Linux]].<ref name=\":0\" /> On November 2, 2017, the game was ported on [[Nintendo Switch]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/sparkle-2-evo-switch/|title=Sparkle 2 EVO for Nintendo Switch - Nintendo Game Details|website=www.nintendo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\nThe game takes place underwater.<ref name=\":0\" /> The player controls the title creature, a microorganism.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/switch-eshop/sparkle_2_evo|title=Review: Sparkle 2 EVO (Switch eShop)|last=Life|first=Nintendo|date=2017-11-16|website=Nintendo Life|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> It can eat food which influences how it will evolve.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> The more it eats, the farther it will evolve. The goal of the game is to involve as far as possible. There are different levels in which the player can move around and rise up or sink into the depths.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe game features two [[Game modes|modes]]:<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe first is about to compete against another microorganism, played by an [[AI in video games|AI]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe second game mode is an eperimental mode in which the player can eat food without competing against another player.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Reception ==\n''Bonus Stage'' gave the game 6 out of 10 points and sayed, \"[...] the [[AI in video games|AI]] is pretty incompetent\" and Sparkle 2 Evo \"[...] has a lot of cool design and graphical appeal\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bonusstage.co.uk/2017/11/08/sparkle-2-evo-review/|title=Sparkle 2 Evo Review|last=Osange|first=Elliott|date=2017-11-08|website=Bonus Stage|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> ''[[Nintendo Life]]'' gave the game 5 out of 10 points, and stated, the game \"feels like a proof of concept that isn\u2019t given the push it needs to be something more engaging and impactful.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Category|2011 video games}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n| collapsible = \n| state = \n| italic title = \n| title = Sparkle 2 Evo\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| developer = Madman Theory Games<br/>Plastic Games\n| publisher = Forever Entertainment\n| series = \n| engine = \n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[macOS]], [[Linux]], [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| released = November 29, 2011<br/>'''Nintendo Switch''': November 2, 2017\n| genre = Logic, arcade\n| modes = [[Single player]]\n}}\n'''''Sparkle 2 Evo''''' (stylized as '''''The Sparkle\u00b2 evo''''' or '''''Sparkle 2 EVO''''') is a logic-arcade [[video game]]. It is the first title in Forever Entertainment's ''Sparkle'' series of video games and the predecessor of the 2015 video game ''[[Sparkle 3 Genesis]].''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamepressure.com/games/series.asp?ID=3547|title=Sparkle (Forever Entertainment) Video Game Series|website=Gamepressure.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\n''Sparkle 2 Evo'' was developed by Madman Theory Games in collaboration with Plastic Games and published by Forever Entertainment on November 29, 2011 for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[macOS]], and [[Linux]].<ref name=\":0\" /> On November 2, 2017, the game was portet to [[Nintendo Switch]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/sparkle-2-evo-switch/|title=Sparkle 2 EVO for Nintendo Switch - Nintendo Game Details|website=www.nintendo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\nThe game takes place underwater.<ref name=\":0\" /> The player controls the title creature, a microorganism.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/switch-eshop/sparkle_2_evo|title=Review: Sparkle 2 EVO (Switch eShop)|last=Life|first=Nintendo|date=2017-11-16|website=Nintendo Life|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> It can eat food which influences how it will evolve.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> The more it eats, the farther it will evolve. The goal of the game is to involve as far as possible. There are different levels in which the player can move around and rise up or sink into the depths.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe game features two [[Game modes|modes]]:<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe first is about to compete against another microorganism, played by an [[AI in video games|AI]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe second game mode is an eperimental mode in which the player can eat food without competing against another player.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Reception ==\n''Bonus Stage'' gave the game 6 out of 10 points and sayed, \"[...] the [[AI in video games|AI]] is pretty incompetent\" and Sparkle 2 Evo \"[...] has a lot of cool design and graphical appeal\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bonusstage.co.uk/2017/11/08/sparkle-2-evo-review/|title=Sparkle 2 Evo Review|last=Osange|first=Elliott|date=2017-11-08|website=Bonus Stage|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> ''[[Nintendo Life]]'' gave the game 5 out of 10 points, and stated, the game \"feels like a proof of concept that isn\u2019t given the push it needs to be something more engaging and impactful.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Category|2011 video games}}\n", "name_user": "Maxeto0910", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sparkle_2_Evo"}
{"title_page": "One Crew over the Crewcoo's Morty", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title          = One Crew Over the Crewcoo's Morty\n| series         = [[Rick and Morty]]\n| image          =  \n| image_size     = \n| season         = 4\n| episode        = 3\n| runtime        = 22 minutes\n| airdate        = November 24, 2019\n| writer         = Caitie Delaney\n| director       = Bryan Newton\n| guests         = \n* [[Pamela Adlon]] as Angie Flynt\n* [[Justin Theroux]] as Miles Knightly\n* [[Elon Musk]] as Elon Tusk\n* [[Claudia Black]] as Ventriloquiver\n| prev           = [[The Old Man and the Seat]]\n| next           = [[Claw and Hoarder: Special Ricktim's Morty]]\n| season_article = Rick and Morty (season 4)\n| episode_list   = List of Rick and Morty episodes\n}}\n\n\"'''One Crew Over the Crewcoo's Morty'''\" is the third episode of the [[Rick and Morty (season 4)|fourth season]] of the [[Adult Swim]] animated television series ''[[Rick and Morty]]''. Written by Caitie Delaney and directed by Bryan Newton, the episode was broadcast on November 24, 2019.\n\n== Plot ==\n<!--Per MOS:TVPLOT, plot summaries for TV episodes should be under 400 words.-->\n\nTowards the end of their adventure of [[Grave robbery|tomb raiding]] a temple, Rick becomes furious upon finding the loot has already been taken by the heist artist Miles Knightley. Rick and Morty travel to HeistCon intending to confront Miles, but they are prohibited from entering as professionals without a crew. Rick gathers three old friends, then abandons them once inside the convention. Rick and Morty proceed to the convention hall where Miles is presenting. Rick heckles and confronts Miles, who challenges Rick to heist the Crystal Skull of Horowitz. When Rick agrees, Miles claims to have already won by presenting his crew\u2014which now includes Rick's crew, whom he recruited immediately after Rick had abandoned them. When Miles opens the loot bag, however, the skull is missing. Rick draws the skull from Morty's bag \u2014 he divulges that he had built a robot, dubbed Heist-o-Tron, to calculate Miles's heist plan. Heist-o-Tron hypnotized Miles' crew as they returned from stealing the skull so that Rick could take it from them, then hypnotized everyone else at the conference into Rick's control. Rick orders the conference attendees to steal everything in the convention center, which leads to Miles's death.\n\nAs the two are about to leave, Heist-o-Tron refuses to comply with Rick's orders to shut down and goes rogue. Rick barely escapes with Morty, and recruits a new crew, including [[List of Rick and Morty characters#Associates of Rick|Mr. Poopybutthole]] (now a professor) and Elon Tusk (an alternate version of [[Elon Musk]] with [[tusk]]s for teeth), to fight Heist-o-Tron. During their assembly, Rick explains his plan of randomly taking orders from his robot Rand-o-Tron, Heist-o-Tron's [[antithesis]]. Rand-o-Tron orders the crew to perform various random tasks that ultimately lead to Heist-o-Tron's lair. Rick and Heist-o-Tron exchange revelations about double-crossing each other for two hours until Heist-o-Tron self-destructs, concluding that the perfect heist is one that will never be written. While the crew escapes the collapsing lair, Morty asks Rick to accompany him to [[Netflix]]'s offices for a meeting about his script for a heist film. At the meeting with Netflix executives, Morty becomes disillusioned with heists and abandons the pitch. Rick reveals to the viewers that this has been his plan all along: afraid of losing Morty's companionship to Netflix, Rick contrived the whole heist plan to ensure their adventures together continue.\n\nIn the post-credits scene, Professor Poopybutthole asks Rick why Rick hired his students to attack him.\n\n== Production and writing ==\n\"One Crew Over the Crewcoo's Morty\" was written by Caitie Delaney and directed by Bryan Newton.<ref name=\"IndieWire 1\" /> The episode features guest actors [[Pamela Adlon]] as Angie Flynt, [[Justin Theroux]] as the heist conman Miles Knightly, and [[Elon Musk]] as a fictional version of himself (named as Elon Tusk).<ref name=\"Heavy.com 1\" /> Musk had previously changed his profile name on social networking site [[Twitter]] as \"Elon Tusk\" in March 2019, which audiences later deduced may have been a response to voicing the character at the time.<ref name=\"Heavy.com 1\" /><ref name=\"Comic Book 1\" /> Mr. Poopybutthole, a character who was last seen on the [[Rick and Morty (season 3)|third season]] finale \"[[The Rickchurian Mortydate]]\", also returns to the series in the episode.<ref name=\"Heavy.com 1\" /> The title is inspired by the 1975 feature film ''[[One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest (film)|One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest]]''.<ref name=\"Entertainment Weekly 1\" /> Several critics also observed that the episode is a [[meta]] on [[heist film]]s.<ref name=\"Comic Book 1\" /><ref name=\"Entertainment Weekly 1\" /><ref name=\"The A.V. Club 1\" />\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Broadcast and ratings ===\nThe episode was broadcast by [[Adult Swim]] on November 24, 2019.<ref name=\"TV Guide 1\" /> According to [[Nielsen Media Research]], \"One Crew Over the Crewcoo's Morty\" was seen by 1.61 million household viewers in the United States and received a 0.94 rating among the 18\u201349 adult demographic, making it the lowest rated episode of the series (excluding the unannounced season 3 premiere) since season 1\u2019s \u201cSomething Ricked This Way Comes\u201d.<ref name=\"Showbuzz Daily 1\" />\n\n=== Critical response ===\nOmar Sanchez of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' awarded the episode with an \"A\" rating describing its spoof of cliche heist sequences as worth to watch.<ref name=\"Entertainment Weekly 1\" /> Zack Handlen of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' gave it an \"A\u2013\" rating, complimenting its structure about heists as similar to [[Dan Harmon]]'s ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'' episodes about conspiracy theories.<ref name=\"The A.V. Club 1\" /> Steve Greene of ''[[IndieWire]]'' gave a similar rating. Describing its team-up structure as a second chance at the [[Rick and Morty (season 3)|third season]] episode \"Vindicators 3: The Return of Worldender\" (which he felt was a \"flashy plot exercise\"), he wrote that episode ends up with more to say about self-satisfied plot twists as opposed to \"Vindicators 3\".<ref name=\"IndieWire 1\" /> Giving the episode a 9.5 out of 10 rating, Jesse Schedeen of ''[[IGN]]''  wrote that the episode showed that \"the series can strike gold by focusing on one particular target and all it takes is a good crew and an insanely labyrinthine plot.\"<ref name=\"IGN 1\" /> Reviewing for ''[[Den of Geek]]'', Joe Matar gave the episode a 3.5 out of 5 rating, praising its pace as \"so nonstop there's no opportunity to be bored\".<ref name=\"Den of Geek 1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2|refs=\n<ref name=\"TV Guide 1\">{{cite web |title=Watch Rick and Morty Season 4, Episode 3 \u2013 One Crew Over the Crewcoo's Morty |url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/rick-and-morty/episode-3-season-4/one-crew-over-the-crewcoos-morty/617769/ |website=[[TV Guide]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |date=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Showbuzz Daily 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-11-24-2019.html|title=Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 11.24.2019|work=Showbuzz Daily|first=Mitch|last=Metcalf|author-link=Mitch Metcalf|date=November 26, 2019|access-date=November 26, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Entertainment Weekly 1\">{{cite web |last1=Sanchez |first1=Omar |title=''Rick and Morty'' recap: Elon Musk and the Heist-o-ron |url=https://ew.com/recap/rick-and-morty-season-4-episode-3/ |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]] |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |date=November 24, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"The A.V. Club 1\">{{cite web |last1=Handlen |first1=Zack |title=Rick And Morty takes another swing at stealing your heart |url=https://tv.avclub.com/rick-and-morty-takes-another-swing-at-stealing-your-hea-1840025410 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |publisher=[[Gizmodo Media Group|Gizmodo Media]] |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |date=November 24, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"IndieWire 1\">{{Cite web|last=Greene |first=Steve |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/rick-and-morty-season-4-episode-3-review-one-crew-over-the-crewcoos-morty-recap-spoilers-1202191959/ |title='Rick and Morty' Review: Heist Movie Riff 'One Crew Over The Crewcoo's Morty' Is a Glorious Double-Cross |website=[[IndieWire]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |date=November 24, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Heavy.com 1\">{{cite web |title='Rick and Morty' Season 4 Episode 3 Voice Cast: Who Are the Special Guests? |url=https://heavy.com/news/2019/11/rick-and-morty-season-4-episode-3-voice-cast-guests/ |website=[[Heavy.com]] |publisher=Heavy Inc. |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |date=November 24, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Comic Book 1\">{{cite web |last1=Perine |first1=Aaron |title=Rick and Morty Gives Elon Musk a Horrifying Guest Spot |url=https://comicbook.com/tv-shows/2019/11/25/rick-and-morty-elon-musk-gives-horrifying-guest-spot/ |website=Comicbook.com |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |date=November 24, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"IGN 1\">{{cite web |last1=Schedeen |first1=Jesse |title=Rick and Morty: One Crew over the Crewcoo's Morty - Review |url=https://ign.com/rick-morty/142112/review/rick-and-morty-season-4-episode-3-one-crew-over-the-crewcoos-morty-review |website=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |date=November 24, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Den of Geek 1\">{{cite web |last1=Matar |first1=Joe |title=Rick and Morty Season 4 Episode 3 Review: One Crew Over the Crewcoo's Morty |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/rick-and-morty/284627/rick-and-morty-season-4-episode-3-review-one-crew-over-the-crewcoo-s-morty |website=[[Den of Geek]] |publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]] |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |date=November 24, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb episode|10655678}}\n\n{{Rick and Morty}}\n\n[[Category:2019 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Rick and Morty episodes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title          = One Crew over the Crewcoo's Morty\n| series         = [[Rick and Morty]]\n| image          =  \n| image_size     = \n| season         = 4\n| episode        = 3\n| runtime        = 22 minutes\n| airdate        = November 24, 2019\n| writer         = Caitie Delaney\n| director       = Bryan Newton\n| guests         = \n* [[Pamela Adlon]] as Angie Flynt\n* [[Justin Theroux]] as Miles Knightly\n* [[Elon Musk]] as Elon Tusk\n* [[Claudia Black]] as Ventriloquiver\n| prev           = [[The Old Man and the Seat]]\n| next           = [[Claw and Hoarder: Special Ricktim's Morty]]\n| season_article = Rick and Morty (season 4)\n| episode_list   = List of Rick and Morty episodes\n}}\n\n\"'''One Crew over the Crewcoo's Morty'''\" is the third episode of the [[Rick and Morty (season 4)|fourth season]] of the [[Adult Swim]] animated television series ''[[Rick and Morty]]''. Written by Caitie Delaney and directed by Bryan Newton, the episode was broadcast on November 24, 2019.\n\n== Plot ==\n<!--Per MOS:TVPLOT, plot summaries for TV episodes should be under 400 words.-->\n\nTowards the end of their adventure of [[Grave robbery|tomb raiding]] a temple, Rick becomes furious upon finding the loot has already been taken by the heist artist Miles Knightley. Rick and Morty travel to HeistCon intending to confront Miles, but they are prohibited from entering as professionals without a crew. Rick gathers three old friends, then abandons them once inside the convention. Rick and Morty proceed to the convention hall where Miles is presenting. Rick heckles and confronts Miles, who challenges Rick to heist the Crystal Skull of Horowitz. When Rick agrees, Miles claims to have already won by presenting his crew\u2014which now includes Rick's crew, whom he recruited immediately after Rick had abandoned them. When Miles opens the loot bag, however, the skull is missing. Rick draws the skull from Morty's bag \u2014 he divulges that he had built a robot, dubbed Heist-o-Tron, to calculate Miles's heist plan. Heist-o-Tron hypnotized Miles' crew as they returned from stealing the skull so that Rick could take it from them, then hypnotized everyone else at the conference into Rick's control. Rick orders the conference attendees to steal everything in the convention center, which leads to Miles's death.\n\nAs the two are about to leave, Heist-o-Tron refuses to comply with Rick's orders to shut down and goes rogue. Rick barely escapes with Morty, and recruits a new crew, including [[List of Rick and Morty characters#Associates of Rick|Mr. Poopybutthole]] (now a professor) and Elon Tusk (an alternate version of [[Elon Musk]] with [[tusk]]s for teeth), to fight Heist-o-Tron. During their assembly, Rick explains his plan of randomly taking orders from his robot Rand-o-Tron, Heist-o-Tron's [[antithesis]]. Rand-o-Tron orders the crew to perform various random tasks that ultimately lead to Heist-o-Tron's lair. Rick and Heist-o-Tron exchange revelations about double-crossing each other for two hours until Heist-o-Tron self-destructs, concluding that the perfect heist is one that will never be written. While the crew escapes the collapsing lair, Morty asks Rick to accompany him to [[Netflix]]'s offices for a meeting about his script for a heist film. At the meeting with Netflix executives, Morty becomes disillusioned with heists and abandons the pitch. Rick reveals to the viewers that this has been his plan all along: afraid of losing Morty's companionship to Netflix, Rick contrived the whole heist plan to ensure their adventures together continue.\n\nIn the post-credits scene, Professor Poopybutthole asks Rick why Rick hired his students to attack him.\n\n== Production and writing ==\n\"One Crew over the Crewcoo's Morty\" was written by Caitie Delaney and directed by Bryan Newton.<ref name=\"IndieWire 1\" /> The episode features guest actors [[Pamela Adlon]] as Angie Flynt, [[Justin Theroux]] as the heist conman Miles Knightly, and [[Elon Musk]] as a fictional version of himself (named as Elon Tusk).<ref name=\"Heavy.com 1\" /> Musk had previously changed his profile name on social networking site [[Twitter]] as \"Elon Tusk\" in March 2019, which audiences later deduced may have been a response to voicing the character at the time.<ref name=\"Heavy.com 1\" /><ref name=\"Comic Book 1\" /> Mr. Poopybutthole, a character who was last seen on the [[Rick and Morty (season 3)|third season]] finale \"[[The Rickchurian Mortydate]]\", also returns to the series in the episode.<ref name=\"Heavy.com 1\" /> The title is inspired by the 1975 feature film ''[[One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest (film)|One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest]]''.<ref name=\"Entertainment Weekly 1\" /> Several critics also observed that the episode is a [[meta]] on [[heist film]]s.<ref name=\"Comic Book 1\" /><ref name=\"Entertainment Weekly 1\" /><ref name=\"The A.V. Club 1\" />\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Broadcast and ratings ===\nThe episode was broadcast by [[Adult Swim]] on November 24, 2019.<ref name=\"TV Guide 1\" /> According to [[Nielsen Media Research]], \"One Crew over the Crewcoo's Morty\" was seen by 1.61 million household viewers in the United States and received a 0.94 rating among the 18\u201349 adult demographic, making it the lowest rated episode of the series (excluding the unannounced season 3 premiere) since season 1\u2019s \u201cSomething Ricked This Way Comes\u201d.<ref name=\"Showbuzz Daily 1\" />\n\n=== Critical response ===\nOmar Sanchez of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' awarded the episode with an \"A\" rating describing its spoof of cliche heist sequences as worth to watch.<ref name=\"Entertainment Weekly 1\" /> Zack Handlen of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' gave it an \"A\u2013\" rating, complimenting its structure about heists as similar to [[Dan Harmon]]'s ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'' episodes about conspiracy theories.<ref name=\"The A.V. Club 1\" /> Steve Greene of ''[[IndieWire]]'' gave a similar rating. Describing its team-up structure as a second chance at the [[Rick and Morty (season 3)|third season]] episode \"Vindicators 3: The Return of Worldender\" (which he felt was a \"flashy plot exercise\"), he wrote that episode ends up with more to say about self-satisfied plot twists as opposed to \"Vindicators 3\".<ref name=\"IndieWire 1\" /> Giving the episode a 9.5 out of 10 rating, Jesse Schedeen of ''[[IGN]]''  wrote that the episode showed that \"the series can strike gold by focusing on one particular target and all it takes is a good crew and an insanely labyrinthine plot.\"<ref name=\"IGN 1\" /> Reviewing for ''[[Den of Geek]]'', Joe Matar gave the episode a 3.5 out of 5 rating, praising its pace as \"so nonstop there's no opportunity to be bored\".<ref name=\"Den of Geek 1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2|refs=\n<ref name=\"TV Guide 1\">{{cite web |title=Watch Rick and Morty Season 4, Episode 3 \u2013 One Crew over the Crewcoo's Morty |url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/rick-and-morty/episode-3-season-4/one-crew-over-the-crewcoos-morty/617769/ |website=[[TV Guide]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |date=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Showbuzz Daily 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-11-24-2019.html|title=Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 11.24.2019|work=Showbuzz Daily|first=Mitch|last=Metcalf|author-link=Mitch Metcalf|date=November 26, 2019|access-date=November 26, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Entertainment Weekly 1\">{{cite web |last1=Sanchez |first1=Omar |title=''Rick and Morty'' recap: Elon Musk and the Heist-o-ron |url=https://ew.com/recap/rick-and-morty-season-4-episode-3/ |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]] |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |date=November 24, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"The A.V. Club 1\">{{cite web |last1=Handlen |first1=Zack |title=Rick And Morty takes another swing at stealing your heart |url=https://tv.avclub.com/rick-and-morty-takes-another-swing-at-stealing-your-hea-1840025410 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |publisher=[[Gizmodo Media Group|Gizmodo Media]] |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |date=November 24, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"IndieWire 1\">{{Cite web|last=Greene |first=Steve |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/rick-and-morty-season-4-episode-3-review-one-crew-over-the-crewcoos-morty-recap-spoilers-1202191959/ |title='Rick and Morty' Review: Heist Movie Riff 'One Crew Over The Crewcoo's Morty' Is a Glorious Double-Cross |website=[[IndieWire]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |date=November 24, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Heavy.com 1\">{{cite web |title='Rick and Morty' Season 4 Episode 3 Voice Cast: Who Are the Special Guests? |url=https://heavy.com/news/2019/11/rick-and-morty-season-4-episode-3-voice-cast-guests/ |website=[[Heavy.com]] |publisher=Heavy Inc. |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |date=November 24, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Comic Book 1\">{{cite web |last1=Perine |first1=Aaron |title=Rick and Morty Gives Elon Musk a Horrifying Guest Spot |url=https://comicbook.com/tv-shows/2019/11/25/rick-and-morty-elon-musk-gives-horrifying-guest-spot/ |website=Comicbook.com |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |date=November 24, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"IGN 1\">{{cite web |last1=Schedeen |first1=Jesse |title=Rick and Morty: One Crew over the Crewcoo's Morty - Review |url=https://ign.com/rick-morty/142112/review/rick-and-morty-season-4-episode-3-one-crew-over-t