{"title_page": "Jon Glover", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|John Glover (actor)}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Jon Glover\n|birth_name = Jonathan Philip Glover\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|12|26|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Crediton]], [[Devon]], [[England]]\n|nationality = British\n|occupation = Actor\n|years_active = 1972\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Jonathan Philip Glover''' (born 26 December 1952) is an English actor. He has appeared in various television programmes including ''[[Play School (UK TV series)|Play School]]'', ''[[Survivors (1975 TV series)|Survivors]]'', the [[Minor characters from The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy#Management consultant|Management consultant]] in ''[[The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy (TV series)|The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy]]'', ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'', ''[[Bodger & Badger]]'' and ''[[Peak Practice]]''.\n\nHe provided the voices of several characters in the [[The Animals of Farthing Wood (TV series)|''Animals of Farthing Wood'' animated series]], and is also known for voice-acting for ''[[Noah's Island]]'', ''[[Spitting Image]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mediatel.co.uk/news/2020/03/05/and-what-about-the-vegetables|title=\u2018And what about the vegetables?\u2019|last=Arnell|first=Stephen|website=mediatel.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> and the character King Trode in the [[English language]] version of the [[PlayStation 2]] game ''[[Dragon Quest VIII]]''. He often appears in radio plays for [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2012/bbc-radio-celebrates-michael-frayns-80th/|title=BBC Radio celebrates Michael Frayn's 80th {{!}} News|last=Hemley|first=Matthew|date=2012-11-01|website=The Stage|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/radio-programme/e/jjk68/mr-standfast--series-1-episode-1/|title=Mr Standfast - S1 - Episode 1|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> He was a regular on the Radio 4 satirical programme ''[[Week Ending]]'' during the 1980s. He played the [[upper class|upper crust]] English character ''Mr Cholmondley-Warner'' in spoof 1940s government documentaries in ''[[Harry Enfield's Television Programme]]'' with excessive [[Received Pronunciation]].\n\nHe also did voices on other animated programmes such as ''[[Little Ghosts]]'', ''[[The Adventures of Paddington Bear]]'', ''[[Mr. Bean (animated TV series)|Mr. Bean]]'' (2002), ''[[Ludwig (cartoon)|Ludwig]]'', ''[[Metalheads (TV series)|Metalheads]]'' and ''[[Rudi and Trudi]]''.\n\nVoices for ''Spitting Image'' included the [[Duke of Edinburgh]], weather forecaster [[Ian McCaskill]], [[Melvyn Bragg]], [[Oliver Reed]], South African State President [[P. W. Botha]] and snooker player [[Steve Davis]].\n\nHis theatre work includes playing Sapiens in a Discovering Lost Musicals concert staging of [[By Jupiter]] at Barbican Cinema 1 in 1992.\n\nHe was featured on the pilot episode of ''[[Whose Line Is It Anyway? (UK TV series)|Whose Line Is It Anyway?]]''.\n\nHe has played theatrical agent Maurice Skellern in BBC Radio 4 adaptations of the [[Simon Brett#Charles Paris|Charles Paris]] mysteries<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00q43nx|title=BBC Radio 4 - A Charles Paris Mystery, Cast in Order of Disappearance, Episode 1|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=gk_g10i|date=2019-09-23|title=Charles Paris: Murder Unprompted: A BBC Radio 4 full-cast dramatisati\u2026|url=https://www.slideshare.net/gk_g10i/charles-paris-murder-unprompted-a-bbc-radio-4-fullcast-dramatisation-mystery-thriller-stories-mystery-thriller-and-horror}}</ref>; and in May 2013 played the roles of Lord Portico & Stockton in a BBC radio adaptation of Neil Gaiman's ''[[Neverwhere (radio play)|Neverwhere]]'', adapted by Dirk Maggs.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0323140|name=Jon Glover}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n\n\n\