radio-celebrates-michael-frayns-80th/|title=BBC Radio celebrates Michael Frayn's 80th {{!}} News|last=Hemley|first=Matthew|date=2012-11-01|website=The Stage|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/radio-programme/e/jjk68/mr-standfast--series-1-episode-1/|title=Mr Standfast - S1 - Episode 1|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> He was a regular on the Radio 4 satirical programme ''[[Week Ending]]'' during the 1980s. He played the [[upper class|upper crust]] English character ''Mr Cholmondley-Warner'' in spoof 1940s government documentaries in ''[[Harry Enfield's Television Programme]]'' with excessive [[Received Pronunciation]].\n\nHe also did voices on other animated programmes such as ''[[Little Ghosts]]'', ''[[The Adventures of Paddington Bear]]'', ''[[Mr. Bean (animated TV series)|Mr. Bean]]'' (2002), ''[[Ludwig (cartoon)|Ludwig]]'', ''[[Metalheads (TV series)|Metalheads]]'' and ''[[Rudi and Trudi]]''.\n\nVoices for ''Spitting Image'' included the [[Duke of Edinburgh]], weather forecaster [[Ian McCaskill]], [[Melvyn Bragg]], [[Oliver Reed]], South African State President [[P. W. Botha]] and snooker player [[Steve Davis]].\n\nHis theatre work includes playing Sapiens in a Discovering Lost Musicals concert staging of [[By Jupiter]] at Barbican Cinema 1 in 1992.\n\nHe was featured on the pilot episode of ''[[Whose Line Is It Anyway? (UK TV series)|Whose Line Is It Anyway?]]''.\n\nHe has played theatrical agent Maurice Skellern in BBC Radio 4 adaptations of the [[Simon Brett#Charles Paris|Charles Paris]] mysteries<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00q43nx|title=BBC Radio 4 - A Charles Paris Mystery, Cast in Order of Disappearance, Episode 1|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=gk_g10i|date=2019-09-23|title=Charles Paris: Murder Unprompted: A BBC Radio 4 full-cast dramatisati\u2026|url=https://www.slideshare.net/gk_g10i/charles-paris-murder-unprompted-a-bbc-radio-4-fullcast-dramatisation-mystery-thriller-stories-mystery-thriller-and-horror}}</ref>; and in May 2013 played the roles of Lord Portico & Stockton in a BBC radio adaptation of Neil Gaiman's ''[[Neverwhere (radio play)|Neverwhere]]'', adapted by Dirk Maggs.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0323140|name=Jon Glover}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Glover, Jon}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Crediton]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Devon]]\n[[Category:BBC television presenters]]\n\n\n{{UK-tv-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cardiffbear88", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jon_Glover"}
{"title_page": "Silvia Fern\u00e1ndez de Gurmendi", "text_new": "{{Infobox Judge\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Silvia Fern\u00e1ndez de Gurmendi\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = Silvia Fern\u00e1ndez de Gurmendi (cropped).jpg\n| caption =\n| order = 3rd\n| office = President of the International Criminal Court\n| term_start = 11 March 2015\n| term_end = 11 March 2018\n| nominator = \n| appointer =\n| predecessor = [[Song Sang-hyun]]\n| successor = [[Chile Eboe-Osuji]]\n| office2 = [[Judges of the International Criminal Court|Judge of the International Criminal Court]]\n| term_start2 = 20 January 2010\n| term_end2 =\n| nominator2 = [[Argentina]]\n| appointer2 =\n| predecessor2 =\n| successor2 =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1954|10|24}}\n| birth_place =[[C\u00f3rdoba Province, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba Province]], [[Argentina]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = [[Argentina|Argentinian]]\n| spouse =\n| party =\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = {{unbulleted list |[[National University of C\u00f3rdoba]] |[[University of Limoges]] |[[University of Buenos Aires]]}}\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Silvia Alejandra Fern\u00e1ndez de Gurmendi''' (born 24 October 1954) is an Argentinian lawyer, diplomat and judge. She has been a judge at the [[International Criminal Court]] (ICC) since 20 January 2010<ref>http://www.icc-cpi.int/Menus/ICC/Structure+of+the+Court/Chambers/The+Judges/The+Judges/Judge+Silvia+FERN%C3%81NDEZ+DE+GURMENDI/Judge+Silvia+Alejandra+FERN%C3%81NDEZ+DE+GURMENDI+_Argentina_.htm</ref> and President of the ICC from March 2015 to March 2018. She was elected to the presidency for a  three-year term and served until March  2018.<ref>[http://www.icc-cpi.int/en_menus/icc/press%20and%20media/press%20releases/Pages/pr1096.aspx \"Judge Fern\u00e1ndez de Gurmendi elected ICC President for 2015-2018; Judges Aluoch and Ozaki elected First and Second Vice-President respectively\"] ICC Press Release</ref>\n\n==Education==\nFern\u00e1ndez studied law at the universities of [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]] and [[Limoges]], and earned a doctorate at the [[University of Buenos Aires]].\n \n==Career==\nFern\u00e1ndez trained as a diplomat 1987\u20131988, and entered the diplomatic service in 1989. In 2006, she became Director General for Human Rights in the Foreign Ministry.\n\n===Judge of the International Criminal Court, 2010-present===\nFern\u00e1ndez was elected as a judge at the ICC on 18 November 2009. During her time as judge, she regularly issued dissenting or partially dissenting opinions in high-profile cases, including opposing the opening of an [[International Criminal Court investigations|ICC investigation in C\u00f4te d'Ivoire]] in 2011.<ref>Peter Cluskey (April 6, 2015), [http://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/international-criminal-court-elects-first-woman-president-1.2164183 International Criminal Court elects first woman president] ''[[The Irish Times]]''.</ref> She served as presiding judge when the ICC rejected [[Libya]]'s request to annul the international arrest warrant for [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi]], ruling that the Libyan government was not yet capable of holding a fair trial by itself and it is obliged under international law to hand him over to the ICC.<ref>Steve Wilson (June 1, 2013), [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/libya/10092894/International-Criminal-Court-rejects-Libyan-government-request-to-try-Saif-al-Islam-Gaddafi.html International Criminal Court rejects Libyan government request to try Saif al-Islam Gaddafi] ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''.</ref> In 2014, as member of the Pre-Trial Chamber I, she later confirmed four charges of [[crimes against humanity]] against former Ivorian minister and youth activist [[Charles Bl\u00e9 Goud\u00e9]] and committed him to trial before a Trial Chamber.<ref>Lisa Bryant (September 29, 2014), [http://www.voanews.com/content/icc-to-decide-on-trial-for-ivorian-youth-leader-ble-goude/2466166.html ICC to Decide on Trial for Ivorian Youth Leader Ble Goude] ''[[Voice of America]]''.</ref>\n\n===President of the International Criminal Court, 2015-present===\nIn early 2015, Fern\u00e1ndez was elected president of the court for a term of three years. Her two vice-presidents, also appointed for three-year terms, are [[Joyce Aluoch]] and [[Kuniko Ozaki]]. With the office of the [[Prosecutor of the International Criminal Court]] held by [[Fatou Bensouda]], four of the court\u2019s most influential legal positions are held by women.<ref>Peter Cluskey (April 6, 2015), [http://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/international-criminal-court-elects-first-woman-president-1.2164183 International Criminal Court elects first woman president] ''[[The Irish Times]]''.</ref>\n\nIn August, Fern\u00e1ndez decided to reopen a hearing into whether to take action against [[Kenya]] over allegations it obstructed investigations into its President [[Uhuru Kenyatta]], arguing that the appeals chamber had failed to properly assess the role of prosecutors and that errors prevented it \"from making a conclusive determination\".<ref>Anthony Deutsch (August 19, 2015), [https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/08/19/us-kenya-court-idUSKCN0QO0RB20150819 Global court to reopen obstruction case against Kenya] ''[[Reuters]]''.</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\nFern\u00e1ndez is also a visiting professor at American University Washington College of Law's [[Academy on Human Rights and Humanitarian Law]]. She is a member of the [[Crimes Against Humanity Initiative]] Advisory Council, a project of the [[Whitney R. Harris World Law Institute]] at [[Washington University in St. Louis | Washington University School of Law in St. Louis]] to establish the world\u2019s first treaty on the prevention and punishment of crimes against humanity.\n\n== Selected publications ==\n* Mit H\u00e5kan Friman: ''The rules of procedure and evidence and the regulations of the court''. In: Jose Doria (Hrsg.): ''The legal regime of the International Criminal Court: essays in honour of Professor Igor Blishchenko; in memoriam Professor Igor Pavlovich Blishchenko (1930-2000)''. Nijhoff, Leiden 2009, {{ISBN|978-90-04-16308-9}}, S.&nbsp;797\u2013824.\n* ''An insider's view''. In: [[Mauro Politi]] (Hrsg.): ''The international criminal court and the crime of aggression''. Aldershot, Ashgate 2004, {{ISBN|0-7546-2362-9}}, S.&nbsp;175&nbsp;ff.\n* Mit H\u00e5kan Friman: ''The rules of procedure and evidence of the International Criminal Court''. In: T.M.C. Asser Instituut, Institute for Private and Public International Law, International Commercial Arbitration and European Law: ''Yearbook of international humanitarian law''. Bd. 3, 2000, {{ISSN|1389-1359}}, S.&nbsp;289\u2013336.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n<ref>IICC webpage</ref>\nhttps://web.archive.org/web/20150502135206/http://www.icc-cpi.int/en_menus/icc/structure%20of%20the%20court/chambers/the%20judges/Pages/judge%20silvia%20alejandra%20fern%C3%A1ndez%20de%20gurmendi.aspx\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fernandez de Gurmendi, Silvia}}\n[[Category:Argentine women judges]]\n[[Category:International Criminal Court judges]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Argentine diplomats]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the International Criminal Court]]\n[[Category:Argentine women diplomats]]\n[[Category:Argentine judges of international courts and tribunals]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Judge\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Silvia Fern\u00e1ndez de Gurmendi\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = Silvia Fern\u00e1ndez de Gurmendi (cropped).jpg\n| caption =\n| order = 3rd\n| office = President of the International Criminal Court\n| term_start = 11 March 2015\n| term_end = 11 March 2018\n| nominator = \n| appointer =\n| predecessor = [[Song Sang-hyun]]\n| successor = [[Chile Eboe-Osuji]]\n| office2 = [[Judges of the International Criminal Court|Judge of the International Criminal Court]]\n| term_start2 = 20 January 2010\n| term_end2 =\n| nominator2 = [[Argentina]]\n| appointer2 =\n| predecessor2 =\n| successor2 =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1954|10|24}}\n| birth_place =[[C\u00f3rdoba Province, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba Province]], [[Argentina]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = [[Argentina|Argentinian]]\n| spouse =\n| party =\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = {{unbulleted list |[[National University of C\u00f3rdoba]] |[[University of Limoges]] |[[University of Buenos Aires]]}}\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Silvia Alejandra Fern\u00e1ndez de Gurmendi''' (born 24 October 1954) is an Argentinian lawyer, diplomat and judge. She has been a judge at the [[International Criminal Court]] (ICC) since 20 January 2010<ref>http://www.icc-cpi.int/Menus/ICC/Structure+of+the+Court/Chambers/The+Judges/The+Judges/Judge+Silvia+FERN%C3%81NDEZ+DE+GURMENDI/Judge+Silvia+Alejandra+FERN%C3%81NDEZ+DE+GURMENDI+_Argentina_.htm</ref> and President of the ICC from March 2015 to March 2018. She was elected to the presidency for a  three-year term and served until March  2018.<ref>[http://www.icc-cpi.int/en_menus/icc/press%20and%20media/press%20releases/Pages/pr1096.aspx \"Judge Fern\u00e1ndez de Gurmendi elected ICC President for 2015-2018; Judges Aluoch and Ozaki elected First and Second Vice-President respectively\"] ICC Press Release</ref>\n\n==Education==\nFern\u00e1ndez studied law at the universities of [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]] and [[Limoges]], and earned a doctorate at the [[University of Buenos Aires]].\n \n==Career==\nFern\u00e1ndez trained as a diplomat 1987\u20131988, and entered the diplomatic service in 1989. In 2006, she became Director General for Human Rights in the Foreign Ministry.\n\n===Judge of the International Criminal Court, 2010-present===\nFern\u00e1ndez was elected as a judge at the ICC on 18 November 2009. During her time as judge, she regularly issued dissenting or partially dissenting opinions in high-profile cases, including opposing the opening of an [[International Criminal Court investigations|ICC investigation in C\u00f4te d'Ivoire]] in 2011.<ref>Peter Cluskey (April 6, 2015), [http://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/international-criminal-court-elects-first-woman-president-1.2164183 International Criminal Court elects first woman president] ''[[The Irish Times]]''.</ref> She served as presiding judge when the ICC rejected [[Libya]]'s request to annul the international arrest warrant for [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi]], ruling that the Libyan government was not yet capable of holding a fair trial by itself and it is obliged under international law to hand him over to the ICC.<ref>Steve Wilson (June 1, 2013), [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/libya/10092894/International-Criminal-Court-rejects-Libyan-government-request-to-try-Saif-al-Islam-Gaddafi.html International Criminal Court rejects Libyan government request to try Saif al-Islam Gaddafi] ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''.</ref> In 2014, as member of the Pre-Trial Chamber I, she later confirmed four charges of [[crimes against humanity]] against former Ivorian minister and youth activist [[Charles Bl\u00e9 Goud\u00e9]] and committed him to trial before a Trial Chamber.<ref>Lisa Bryant (September 29, 2014), [http://www.voanews.com/content/icc-to-decide-on-trial-for-ivorian-youth-leader-ble-goude/2466166.html ICC to Decide on Trial for Ivorian Youth Leader Ble Goude] ''[[Voice of America]]''.</ref>\n\n===President of the International Criminal Court, 2015-present===\nIn early 2015, Fern\u00e1ndez was elected president of the court for a term of three years. Her two vice-presidents, also appointed for three-year terms, are [[Joyce Aluoch]] and [[Kuniko Ozaki]]. With the office of the [[Prosecutor of the International Criminal Court]] held by [[Fatou Bensouda]], four of the court\u2019s most influential legal positions are held by women.<ref>Peter Cluskey (April 6, 2015), [http://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/international-criminal-court-elects-first-woman-president-1.2164183 International Criminal Court elects first woman president] ''[[The Irish Times]]''.</ref>\n\nIn August, Fern\u00e1ndez decided to reopen a hearing into whether to take action against [[Kenya]] over allegations it obstructed investigations into its President [[Uhuru Kenyatta]], arguing that the appeals chamber had failed to properly assess the role of prosecutors and that errors prevented it \"from making a conclusive determination\".<ref>Anthony Deutsch (August 19, 2015), [https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/08/19/us-kenya-court-idUSKCN0QO0RB20150819 Global court to reopen obstruction case against Kenya] ''[[Reuters]]''.</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\nFern\u00e1ndez is also a visiting professor at American University Washington College of Law's [[Academy on Human Rights and Humanitarian Law]].\n\n== Selected publications ==\n* Mit H\u00e5kan Friman: ''The rules of procedure and evidence and the regulations of the court''. In: Jose Doria (Hrsg.): ''The legal regime of the International Criminal Court: essays in honour of Professor Igor Blishchenko; in memoriam Professor Igor Pavlovich Blishchenko (1930-2000)''. Nijhoff, Leiden 2009, {{ISBN|978-90-04-16308-9}}, S.&nbsp;797\u2013824.\n* ''An insider's view''. In: [[Mauro Politi]] (Hrsg.): ''The international criminal court and the crime of aggression''. Aldershot, Ashgate 2004, {{ISBN|0-7546-2362-9}}, S.&nbsp;175&nbsp;ff.\n* Mit H\u00e5kan Friman: ''The rules of procedure and evidence of the International Criminal Court''. In: T.M.C. Asser Instituut, Institute for Private and Public International Law, International Commercial Arbitration and European Law: ''Yearbook of international humanitarian law''. Bd. 3, 2000, {{ISSN|1389-1359}}, S.&nbsp;289\u2013336.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n<ref>IICC webpage</ref>\nhttps://web.archive.org/web/20150502135206/http://www.icc-cpi.int/en_menus/icc/structure%20of%20the%20court/chambers/the%20judges/Pages/judge%20silvia%20alejandra%20fern%C3%A1ndez%20de%20gurmendi.aspx\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fernandez de Gurmendi, Silvia}}\n[[Category:Argentine women judges]]\n[[Category:International Criminal Court judges]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Argentine diplomats]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the International Criminal Court]]\n[[Category:Argentine women diplomats]]\n[[Category:Argentine judges of international courts and tribunals]]\n", "name_user": "Freyarhianne", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silvia_Fern%C3%A1ndez_de_Gurmendi"}
{"title_page": "Masoud Khalili", "text_new": "{{Infobox Ambassador\n|name         = Masoud Khalili<br/>{{Nobold|{{lang|fa|\u0645\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f \u062e\u0644\u06cc\u0644\u06cc}}}}\n|image        =\n|imagesize    = \n|alt          = \n|order        = \n|office       = Afghanistan Ambassador to Spain\n|term_start   = 2010\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = Gul Ahmad Sherzada\n|successor    = \n|president    = [[Hamid Karzai]]\n|office2       = Afghanistan Ambassador to Turkey\n|term_start2   = 2007\n|term_end2    = 2010\n|predecessor2  = \n|successor2    = [[Salahuddin Rabbani]]\n|president2    = [[Hamid Karzai]]\n|office3       = [[Afghan Ambassador to India]]\n|term_start3   = 2001\n|term_end3    = 2006\n|predecessor3  = \n|successor3  = [[Sayed Makhdoom Raheen]]\n|president3    = [[Hamid Karzai]]\n|birth_date   = \n|birth_place  = [[Parwan Province]], [[Afghanistan]]\n|birthname    = \n|nationality  = Afghan\n|party        = [[Jamiat-i Islami]]\n|otherparty   = \n|spouse       = \n|children     = \n|residence    = \n|alma_mater   = \n|occupation   = [[Ambassador]]\n|profession   = \n|cabinet      = \n|committees   = \n|portfolio    = \n|religion     = [[Islam]]\n|signature    = \n|signature_alt= \n|website      = \n|footnotes    = \n}}\n\n'''Masoud Khalili''', also '''Massoud Khalili''' and '''Masud Khalili''' ({{lang-fa|\u0645\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f \u062e\u0644\u06cc\u0644\u06cc}}; born 5 November 1950) is an Afghan diplomat, linguist and urbane poet. Khalili is the son of the famous Dari language and Afghan poet laureate, Ustad Khalilullah Khalili.<ref>https://www.amazon.com/Memoirs-Khalilullah-Khalili-Philosopher-Conversation/dp/0615889727</ref>  In the war against the Soviets from 1980 to 1990, he was the political head of the Jamiat-i-Islami Party of Afghanistan and close advisor to Commander Ahmad Shah Masood.<ref>http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2014/09/afghanistan-shadow-ahmad-shah-mas-2014997826874331.html</ref> In the internal conflict that followed, he chose to be the Special Envoy in Pakistan to President Burhannudin Rabbani. Deported from the same country for his high rank in the Northern Alliance, he went to New Delhi in 1996 as the Ambassador of the Afghanistan (Anti-Taliban) where he stayed for many years. He was non-resident Ambassador to Sri Lanka and Nepal at the same time.<ref name=\"masoodkhalili.com\">http://www.masoodkhalili.com</ref> \n \nOn September 9, 2001, Ambassador Khalili was sitting next to Commander [[Ahmad Shah Massoud]] when two men posing as journalists set off a bomb placed in their camera. Commander Massoud was assassinated and Ambassador Khalili survived. Two days later, Al Qaeda Attacked America.<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/afghanistan/1360632/Blast-survivor-tells-of-Massoud-assassination.html</ref> \n \nAfter his recovery, he was made the Ambassador of Afghanistan to Turkey and he is currently the first Afghan Ambassador to Spain. You can find further information about him by visiting his official website<ref name=\"masoodkhalili.com\"/> or official Facebook page.<ref>https://www.facebook.com/pages/Masood-Khalili-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%AE%D9%84%DB%8C%D9%84%DB%8C/361643033965832</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKhalili is the son of the famous [[Persian language]] poet, and [[Persian language|Persian]] poet laureate, [[Khalilullah Khalili|Ustad Khalilullah Khalili]]. Born in [[Jabal Saraj]], [[Parwan Province]] in [[Kingdom of Afghanistan|Afghanistan]], Massoud Khalili grew up in [[Kabul]] where his father taught at [[Kabul University]]. As a student he reportedly spent 5 years in India.<Ref Name=\"Afghan Bios\">\n{{Cite web |url=http://www.afghan-bios.info/tinc?key=2vB1wwzV&session_currentpage=index&session_mode=guest&formname=afghan_bios&session_searchcriteria=khalili&session_sortby=field_3&userid=1280780232;702528;38&session_nextpage=data_edit&session_offset=50&session_start=1&session_dbkey=1255208196;601803;856_afghan_bios&dbkey=1255208196;601803;856_afghan_bios |title=Afghan Bios:Khalili, Masood |access-date=2010-08-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718130548/http://www.afghan-bios.info/tinc?key=2vB1wwzV&session_currentpage=index&session_mode=guest&formname=afghan_bios&session_searchcriteria=khalili&session_sortby=field_3&userid=1280780232;702528;38&session_nextpage=data_edit&session_offset=50&session_start=1&session_dbkey=1255208196;601803;856_afghan_bios&dbkey=1255208196;601803;856_afghan_bios |archive-date=2011-07-18 |url-status=dead }}\n</ref> Khalili got his BA in Delhi College and MA from Kirori Mal College in the 70s.<Ref Name=\"Afghan Bios\" />\n\n==Resistance against Invasion==\nKhalili was a friend and adviser to [[Ahmad Shah Massoud]], resistance commander known as the \"Lion of Panjshir\" against the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan (1979\u20131989), defense minister of Afghanistan (1992\u20132001) and leader of the United Front ([[Northern Alliance]]) against the Taliban.\n\nKhalili and Massoud met for the first time in October 1978 after the communist [[Saur Revolution]] had overthrown the government of [[Mohammed Daoud Khan]].<ref name=\"Webster University Press Book\">{{cite book | last = Marcela Grad| authorlink = | title = Massoud: An Intimate Portrait of the Legendary Afghan Leader|edition=March 1, 2009 |pages=310  | publisher = Webster University Press| isbn= }}</ref> Khalili remembers: \n::\"We talked about the past and the future. I was talking more, maybe because I was older, but I found out later that listening was his habit.\"<ref name=\"Webster University Press Book\"/>\nBoth men quickly discovered their shared interest for poetry.<ref name=\"Webster University Press Book\"/>\n\nAfter the meeting Khalili went on to live in the United States for two years where his father, [[Khalilullah Khalili|Ustad Khalilullah Khalili]], was serving as the ambassador to the United States.<ref name=\"Webster University Press Book\"/> In 1980 he went back to Afghanistan to join Ahmad Shah Massoud's resistance against the [[Soviet invasion of Afghanistan]] (1979\u20131989).<ref name=\"Webster University Press Book\"/> Khalili remembers:\n::\"I wrote in my diary that I found something in him [Massoud] very vivid, distinguished, and strong: the hope he has for the liberation of Afghanistan. I wrote, \"He is on the move, and while he is watching the mighty power of the Russians and their arsenal, he is planning how to defeat it with commitment. [...] we talked about how to reach the people of the world and convince them that the Afghan people would stand whether they helped or not. They would stand by their own will and would continue the fight to victory, whether others wanted it or not.\"<ref name=\"Webster University Press Book\"/>\n\nIn the 1980s Masood Khalili became a spokesperson and interpreter for Ahmad Shah Massoud.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=cWgeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=78cEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1394,235500&dq=massoud-khalili&hl=en Times Dailey: Rebels: Soviets Bogged Down In Afghanistan]</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5wkhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=WXIFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1748,6286310&dq=massoud-khalili&hl=en Afghans lost major battle by trying to stand, fight]</ref> He traveled Afghanistan, Pakistan and Europe as a diplomat for the resistance. Massoud went on to defeat nine major offensives by the Soviet Red Army. When the Soviets retreated from Afghanistan, the [[Wall Street Journal]] named him \"the Afghan, who won the cold war\".<ref name=\"Charlie Rose\">{{cite web|year=2001 |url =http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=2911290068493351924# |title = Charlie Rose, March 2001, citing Wall Street Journal around 40:00 ff.| publisher = [[Charlie Rose]]}}</ref>\n\nMasood Khalili describes [[Civil war in Afghanistan (1992-1996)|the period after the Soviet withdrawal]] with the following words:\n::\"The communist retreat from Kabul marked the end of one war and the beginning of another. [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]] was just beyond the capital, and that chapter would be very dark, bloody, and brutal. [...] Those were the worst years for us, and I think certainly the worst for Commander Massoud. [...] Whenever you go back to the years 1992 to 1996, you find this chapter of Afghanistan full of blood. But, why do people call it a \"civil\" war? [...] Unfortunately, Iran was helping one [...] group, Uzbekistan was helping another group, and Pakistan was helping another - Hekmatyar. They made up something like a council of solidarity [...] The Commander [who had been appointed as Afghan minister of defense in 1992 by the peace and power-sharing agreement, the Peshawar Accords,] was almost alone with his own forces. [...] The various forces fighting the government [also established by the Peshawar Accords] were all supported by neighboring countries who had their own interests and wanted us to fight each other [...]\"<ref name=\"Webster University Press Book\"/>\nMasood Khalili again started to work around Massoud as an adviser, interpreter and envoy - \"as a soldier without a gun\" as he calls it himself.<ref name=\"Webster University Press Book\"/> In 1995 Khalili served as the [[Islamic State of Afghanistan]] governments's envoy to Pakistan for President [[Burhanuddin Rabbani]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1995/02/12/world/afghanistan-s-warring-factions-agree-to-form-a-ruling-council.html NY Times: Afghanistan's Warring Factions Agree to Form a Ruling Council]</ref> Relations between the Islamic State of Afghanistan and Pakistan were tense because of the latter's support to [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]] and the [[Taliban]]. In late 1995 Pakistan's government expelled Khalili in what the Washington Post called \"the latest sign of worsening relations between the two countries\".<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/19416437.html?dids=19416437:19416437&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+10%2C+1995&author=&pub=The+Washington+Post+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&desc=Pakistan+Expels+Afghan+Envoy&pqatl=google Washington Post: Pakistan Expels Afghan Envoy]</ref>\n\nOn September 27, 1996, the [[Taliban]] seized power in Kabul with military support by Pakistan and financial support by Saudi Arabia and established the [[Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan]].<ref>Coll, ''Ghost Wars'' (New York: Penguin, 2005), 14.</ref> The Taliban Emirate received no diplomatic recognition from the international community (except from Saudi Arabia, Pakistan and the United Arab Emirates). The United Nations and the international community kept recognition with the [[Islamic State of Afghanistan]] government Masood Khalili was working for. The Taliban imposed on the parts of Afghanistan under their control their political and judicial interpretation of Islam issuing edicts forbidding women to work outside the home, attend school, or to leave their homes unless accompanied by a male relative.<ref name=\"Physicians for Human Rights\">{{cite web |year=1998 |url=http://physiciansforhumanrights.org/library/documents/reports/talibans-war-on-women.pdf |title=The Taliban's War on Women. A Health and Human Rights Crisis in Afghanistan |publisher=[[Physicians for Human Rights]] |access-date=2010-11-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702234326/http://physiciansforhumanrights.org/library/documents/reports/talibans-war-on-women.pdf |archive-date=2007-07-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Physicians for Human Rights (PHR) analyze:\n\n{{blockquote|To PHR\u2019s knowledge, no other regime in the world has methodically and violently forced half of its population into virtual house arrest, prohibiting them on pain of physical punishment.<ref name=\"Physicians for Human Rights\"/>}}\n\nMasood Khalili was not in Kabul during that time but he recalls a phone call he got from Massoud:\n::\"He said: \"Did you hear that we left Kabul?\" \"Yes. Are you okay? Are the others okay?\" \"Yes,\" and he added, \"We'll go back.\" Then he asked: \"Do you have something in mind to tell me?\" [...] I told him a verse of my father's that night:\n:::''Oh the cruel, the despot, the oppressor!''\n:::''I will not indeed be giving that to the one who wants to destroy me.''\n:::''You will see me in another battle, in another time,''\n:::''Because God has given hope to my heart,''\n:::''And this hope will bring me back to what I want to reach.''\n::\"That is what I wanted. Hope will take us back! It's good that you have told me this tonight. Thank you very much.\"\n\nDefense minister Ahmad Shah Massoud created the United Front ([[Northern Alliance]]) in opposition to the Taliban regime. The [[Civil war in Afghanistan (1996-2001)|resistance against the Taliban]] was joined by leaders of all Afghan ethnicities and backgrounds. The Taliban committed massacres killing thousands of civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports98/afghan/Afrepor0-03.htm#P186_38364 |title=INCITEMENT OF VIOLENCE AGAINST HAZARAS BY GOVERNOR NIAZI |accessdate=December 27, 2007 |author= Human Rights Watch|authorlink= Human Rights Watch|date=November 1998|work=AFGHANISTAN: THE MASSACRE IN MAZAR-I SHARIF |publisher= hrw.org}}</ref> As a consequence many civilians fled to the area of [[Ahmad Shah Massoud]].<ref>{{cite web|year=2007 |url=http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/episode/inside-the-taliban-3274/Overview |title=Inside the Taliban |publisher=[[National Geographic Channel|National Geographic]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080929130330/http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/episode/inside-the-taliban-3274/Overview |archivedate=2008-09-29 }}</ref><ref name=\"National Geographic\">{{cite web|year=2007|url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xpQI6HKV-ZY |title = Inside the Taliban| publisher = [[National Geographic Channel|National Geographic]]}}</ref> [[National Geographic Channel|National Geographic]] concluded in its documentary ''\"Inside the Taliban\"'':\n{{blockquote|\"The only thing standing in the way of future Taliban massacres is [[Ahmad Shah Massoud]].\"<ref name=\"National Geographic\"/>}}\nKhalili remained an adviser to [[Ahmad Shah Massoud]].<ref>MacFarquhar, Emily (12 November 1990) \"Praise Allah and pass the ammunition\" ''U.S. News & World Report'' 109(19): p. 54</ref> In 1996 he was appointed as ambassador of the United Front to India.<ref name=\"DT-9-01\">Rashid, Ahmed (11 September 2001) \"Afghanistan resistance leader feared dead in blast\" ''Daily Telegraph'' London, p. 11</ref><ref name=\"TimesIndia01\">Talwar, Ashwani (26 October 2001) \"Khalili Remembers Fatal Attack on Massood\" ''The Times of India''</ref><ref name=\"NYT01\">Dugger, Celia W. (26 October 2001) \"A Nation Challenged: the Survivor: Taliban Foe Tells of Calm, Quiet Assassins\" ''The New York Times'' p. B-2</ref>\n\n==September 9, 2001==\nIn September 2001, while preparing against planned offensives by the Taliban in Takhar province, Ahmed Shah Massoud asked Masood Khalili to come over to [[Takhar]] to advise him.<ref name=\"CSMonitor\">[http://www.csmonitor.com/2002/0220/p07s01-wosc.html CS Monitor: Myth of Masood endures in Afghan halls of power]</ref>\n\nSpeaking to BBC correspondent [[Lyse Doucet]] Masood Khalili recalled the morning of the 9th of September 2001:\n\n::\"The night before that [the assassination] we talked for about three-four hours until 3.30 in the morning. Around that time he told me, Let us open the book and see what will happen - a poetry book that he had, he opened it - it's a kind of telling fortune, from [[Hafez]], the great poet, [[Iran|Persian]] poet. And mostly in Afghanistan we open his book and see what happens to our future. And then I opened it and it came that ... 'Take out from your heart all the siblings of enmity, plant the tree and seed of love - Tonight you two are together. Valuate, many nights go, many days disappear. You two will not be able to see each other again'.<ref name =\"BBC Radio 4\">''One to One'' interview with Lyse Doucet, Tuesday 11th October 2011, BBC Radio 4</ref>\n\nElsewhere he recalls:\n\n::\"The ... morning around ten he came to my room. My passport was lying on the bed. He told me to put my passport in my shirt pocket. [...] We went to the river that divides central Asia and Afghanistan, the Amu Darya. He told me two Arabs were there for an interview. ... We went in and he was on my left. The cameraman was in front of us. I remember the pious smile of the photographer ... And after five minutes he died and I survived.\"<ref name=\"The Orange County Register\">[http://www.afghanrelief.org/pdf/Lynch2003.pdf Tulips in a Minefield] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724225131/http://www.afghanrelief.org/pdf/Lynch2003.pdf |date=2011-07-24 }}</ref>\nOn September 9, 2001, Khalili interpreted for Massoud while he was interviewed by two Tunisians allegedly belonging to [[Al Qaeda]] posing as journalists.<ref name=\"TimesIndia01\"/><ref name=\"NYT01\"/><ref>Anderson, Jon Lee (10 June 2002) \"The Assassins: Who was involved in the murder of Ahmed Shah Massoud?\" ''The New Yorker''</ref> During the interview the suicide assassins detonated a bomb hidden in the video camera.<ref name=\"DT-9-01\"/><ref name=\"TimesIndia01\"/><ref name=\"NYT01\"/><ref name=\"NYT01\"/><ref name =\"CNN\">[http://archives.cnn.com/2001/WORLD/asiapcf/central/10/06/bindra.focus/ Witness recalls assassination of anti-Taliban leader]</ref> Ahmad Shah Massoud died in a helicopter that was taking him and Khalili to hospital. Another aide of Massoud also died in the attack. The ''Los Angeles Times'' writes: \"The explosion left Khalili blind in his right eye, deaf in his right ear and badly burned over much of his body, which was peppered by about 1,000 pieces of shrapnel. About 300 pieces are still in his left leg.\"<ref name=\"LA Times\">[http://articles.latimes.com/2002/sep/11/nation/na-911khalili11LA Times: Masood Khalili]</ref> \nThe passport, which Massoud had told him to put into his shirt pocket, had stopped eight pieces of shrapnel from entering Khalili's heart and had thereby saved his life. \n::\"God saved me, but always God is helped by some means.\"<ref name=\"The Orange County Register\"/>\nAbout the death of Massoud he said:\n::\"When you are buried in the hearts of the people, you are always alive.\"\n::\"Whenever you fight for the right cause, if you die, you don't die. But if you fight for the wrong cause, you never live.\"<ref name=\"The Orange County Register\"/>\nTwo days later the attacks of September 11, 2001, killed 3000 people on U.S. soil.\n\n==Recent Activities==\nAfter the fall of the Taliban regime Masood Khalili served as the ambassador of [[Afghanistan]] to India from 2001 to 2006.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.afghan-web.com/politics/embassies.html |title=\"Embassies of Afghanistan\" |access-date=2008-01-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902035655/http://www.afghan-web.com/politics/embassies.html |archive-date=2011-09-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2007 he was appointed as ambassador to Turkey.<ref name=\"\u00e4fghan web\">[http://www.afghan-web.com/bios/today/others.html#Mkhalili] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026121324/http://www.afghan-web.com/bios/today/others.html#Mkhalili |date=2016-10-26 }} Afghan Web: Other Important Personalities of Today]</ref> To promote the Afghan Culture, Khalili recently translated a book of poems of his father [[Khalilullah Khalili|Ustad Khalilullah Khalili]] into English.<ref>[http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/english/lifestyle/11101961.asp?scr=1 \u2019Assembly of Moths\u2019 by Afghan poet now in Turkish]</ref> About the presence of foreign troops in Afghanistan he said in 2008:\n::\"[T]hose boys give their lives for Afghanistan; a boy from America, Holland, France giving his life, we always admire him. [...] I wish he [Massoud] could be alive today, to see the world is now helping Afghanistan.\"<ref name=\"afghanistanhelp\">[https://groups.yahoo.com/group/afghanistanhelp/message/161 Massoud Khalili at Massoud gathering: \"Afghanistanis admire Dutch soldiers\"]</ref>\n\nAbout the struggle of his country he stated in 2006:\n\n::\"[W]e should not again be interfered with, covertly or overtly, by any neighbouring country. They have the potential to destabilise us. If that is stopped, leave the country to the Afghans. We will make many mistakes but ultimately we will come through. [...] Give us time. After 25 years of war, at least give us 20 years to stand again. This is not easy. The people want to live in peace. Help us with our economy, just so that we can stand again. [...] For 25 years people have seen war. They have lost 1.5 million people. Imagine it -- the pain of the loss of a brother, the loss of a son. We have a phrase that you will never know the fire as long as you are not in it. May God not put any country in the fire that we were in.\"<ref>[http://in.rediff.com/news/2006/feb/03inter1.htm 'May God not put any country in the fire that we were in']</ref>\n\nKhalili was later appointed Afghan ambassador to Spain in 2010. In August 2019 he was mugged on the street in [[Barcelona]] suffering a leg injury while in the city to attend celebrations marking Afghanistan's Independence Day.<ref name=\"pajhwok\">[https://www.pajhwok.com/en/2019/08/20/afghan-ambassador-mugged-barcelona Afghan ambassador mugged in Barcelona\"]</ref> His \u20ac17,000 watch was stolen as part of a significant increase in aggressive petty thefts in the city.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.majorcadailybulletin.com/news/international/2019/08/22/57281/alert-from-the-embassy-due-crime-barcelona.html|title=Alert from the U.S. Embassy due to crime in Barcelona|accessdate=22 August 2019|publisher=Majorca Daily Bulletin}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<!--<nowiki> \nSee http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes for an explanation of how to generate footnotes using the <ref> and </ref> tags.\n</nowiki>-->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{YouTube|NwrAcbHBMXc|Masood Khalili at the 7th death anniversary of Ahmad Shah Massoud}} video\n*{{YouTube|N667V8Y6oNQ|Masood Khalili interpreting between Ahmad Shah Massoud and Javier Solana (EU)}} video\n*{{YouTube|JLsbavEJCTM|Ahmad Shah Massoud with a delegation of Afghan national unity (including Masood Khalili) in Europe 2001}} video\n*[http://www.jezail.org/02_dreamsmith2001/31AF_KLILI.html \"Massoud Khalili 1988\"] photo and commentary\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{AfghanDiplomats}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khalili, Masood}}\n[[Category:Afghan politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Afghan Tajik people]]\n[[Category:People from Parwan Province]]\n[[Category:Afghan expatriates in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Afghanistan to India]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Afghanistan to Turkey]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Afghanistan to Spain]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Ambassador\n|name         = Masoud Khalili<br/>{{Nobold|{{lang|fa|\u0645\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f \u062e\u0644\u06cc\u0644\u06cc}}}}\n|image        =\n|imagesize    = \n|alt          = \n|order        = \n|office       = Afghanistan Ambassador to Spain\n|term_start   = 2010\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = Gul Ahmad Sherzada\n|successor    = \n|president    = [[Hamid Karzai]]\n|office2       = Afghanistan Ambassador to Turkey\n|term_start2   = 2007\n|term_end2    = 2010\n|predecessor2  = \n|successor2    = [[Salahuddin Rabbani]]\n|president2    = [[Hamid Karzai]]\n|office3       = [[Afghan Ambassador to India]]\n|term_start3   = 2001\n|term_end3    = 2006\n|predecessor3  = \n|successor3  = [[Sayed Makhdoom Raheen]]\n|president3    = [[Hamid Karzai]]\n|birth_date   = \n|birth_place  = [[Parwan Province]], [[Afghanistan]]\n|birthname    = \n|nationality  = Afghan\n|party        = [[Jamiat-i Islami]]\n|otherparty   = \n|spouse       = \n|children     = \n|residence    = \n|alma_mater   = \n|occupation   = [[Ambassador]]\n|profession   = \n|cabinet      = \n|committees   = \n|portfolio    = \n|religion     = [[Islam]]\n|signature    = \n|signature_alt= \n|website      = \n|footnotes    = \n}}\n\n'''Masoud Khalili''', also '''Massoud Khalili''' and '''Masud Khalili''' ({{lang-fa|\u0645\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f \u062e\u0644\u06cc\u0644\u06cc}}; born 5 November 1950) is an Afghan diplomat, linguist and urbane poet. Khalili is the son of the famous Dari language and Afghan poet laureate, Ustad Khalilullah Khalili.<ref>https://www.amazon.com/Memoirs-Khalilullah-Khalili-Philosopher-Conversation/dp/0615889727</ref>  In the war against the Soviets from 1980 to 1990, he was the political head of the Jamiat-i-Islami Party of Afghanistan and close advisor to Commander Ahmad Shah Masood.<ref>http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2014/09/afghanistan-shadow-ahmad-shah-mas-2014997826874331.html</ref> In the internal conflict that followed, he chose to be the Special Envoy in Pakistan to President Burhannudin Rabbani. Deported from the same country for his high rank in the Northern Alliance, he went to New Delhi in 1996 as the Ambassador of the Afghanistan (Anti-Taliban) where he stayed for many years. He was non-resident Ambassador to Sri Lanka and Nepal at the same time.<ref name=\"masoodkhalili.com\">http://www.masoodkhalili.com</ref> \n \nOn September 9, 2001, Ambassador Khalili was sitting next to Commander Massoud when two men posing as journalists set off a bomb placed in their camera. Commander Massoud was assassinated and Ambassador Khalili survived. Two days later, Al Qaeda Attacked America.<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/afghanistan/1360632/Blast-survivor-tells-of-Massoud-assassination.html</ref> \n \nAfter his recovery, he was made the Ambassador of Afghanistan to Turkey and he is currently the first Afghan Ambassador to Spain. You can find further information about him by visiting his official website<ref name=\"masoodkhalili.com\"/> or official Facebook page.<ref>https://www.facebook.com/pages/Masood-Khalili-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%AE%D9%84%DB%8C%D9%84%DB%8C/361643033965832</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKhalili is the son of the famous [[Persian language]] poet, and [[Persian language|Persian]] poet laureate, [[Khalilullah Khalili|Ustad Khalilullah Khalili]]. Born in [[Jabal Saraj]], [[Parwan Province]] in [[Kingdom of Afghanistan|Afghanistan]], Massoud Khalili grew up in [[Kabul]] where his father taught at [[Kabul University]]. As a student he reportedly spent 5 years in India.<Ref Name=\"Afghan Bios\">\n{{Cite web |url=http://www.afghan-bios.info/tinc?key=2vB1wwzV&session_currentpage=index&session_mode=guest&formname=afghan_bios&session_searchcriteria=khalili&session_sortby=field_3&userid=1280780232;702528;38&session_nextpage=data_edit&session_offset=50&session_start=1&session_dbkey=1255208196;601803;856_afghan_bios&dbkey=1255208196;601803;856_afghan_bios |title=Afghan Bios:Khalili, Masood |access-date=2010-08-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718130548/http://www.afghan-bios.info/tinc?key=2vB1wwzV&session_currentpage=index&session_mode=guest&formname=afghan_bios&session_searchcriteria=khalili&session_sortby=field_3&userid=1280780232;702528;38&session_nextpage=data_edit&session_offset=50&session_start=1&session_dbkey=1255208196;601803;856_afghan_bios&dbkey=1255208196;601803;856_afghan_bios |archive-date=2011-07-18 |url-status=dead }}\n</ref> Khalili got his BA in Delhi College and MA from Kirori Mal College in the 70s.<Ref Name=\"Afghan Bios\" />\n\n==Resistance against Invasion==\nKhalili was a friend and adviser to [[Ahmad Shah Massoud]], resistance commander known as the \"Lion of Panjshir\" against the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan (1979\u20131989), defense minister of Afghanistan (1992\u20132001) and leader of the United Front ([[Northern Alliance]]) against the Taliban.\n\nKhalili and Massoud met for the first time in October 1978 after the communist [[Saur Revolution]] had overthrown the government of [[Mohammed Daoud Khan]].<ref name=\"Webster University Press Book\">{{cite book | last = Marcela Grad| authorlink = | title = Massoud: An Intimate Portrait of the Legendary Afghan Leader|edition=March 1, 2009 |pages=310  | publisher = Webster University Press| isbn= }}</ref> Khalili remembers: \n::\"We talked about the past and the future. I was talking more, maybe because I was older, but I found out later that listening was his habit.\"<ref name=\"Webster University Press Book\"/>\nBoth men quickly discovered their shared interest for poetry.<ref name=\"Webster University Press Book\"/>\n\nAfter the meeting Khalili went on to live in the United States for two years where his father, [[Khalilullah Khalili|Ustad Khalilullah Khalili]], was serving as the ambassador to the United States.<ref name=\"Webster University Press Book\"/> In 1980 he went back to Afghanistan to join Ahmad Shah Massoud's resistance against the [[Soviet invasion of Afghanistan]] (1979\u20131989).<ref name=\"Webster University Press Book\"/> Khalili remembers:\n::\"I wrote in my diary that I found something in him [Massoud] very vivid, distinguished, and strong: the hope he has for the liberation of Afghanistan. I wrote, \"He is on the move, and while he is watching the mighty power of the Russians and their arsenal, he is planning how to defeat it with commitment. [...] we talked about how to reach the people of the world and convince them that the Afghan people would stand whether they helped or not. They would stand by their own will and would continue the fight to victory, whether others wanted it or not.\"<ref name=\"Webster University Press Book\"/>\n\nIn the 1980s Masood Khalili became a spokesperson and interpreter for Ahmad Shah Massoud.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=cWgeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=78cEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1394,235500&dq=massoud-khalili&hl=en Times Dailey: Rebels: Soviets Bogged Down In Afghanistan]</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5wkhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=WXIFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1748,6286310&dq=massoud-khalili&hl=en Afghans lost major battle by trying to stand, fight]</ref> He traveled Afghanistan, Pakistan and Europe as a diplomat for the resistance. Massoud went on to defeat nine major offensives by the Soviet Red Army. When the Soviets retreated from Afghanistan, the [[Wall Street Journal]] named him \"the Afghan, who won the cold war\".<ref name=\"Charlie Rose\">{{cite web|year=2001 |url =http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=2911290068493351924# |title = Charlie Rose, March 2001, citing Wall Street Journal around 40:00 ff.| publisher = [[Charlie Rose]]}}</ref>\n\nMasood Khalili describes [[Civil war in Afghanistan (1992-1996)|the period after the Soviet withdrawal]] with the following words:\n::\"The communist retreat from Kabul marked the end of one war and the beginning of another. [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]] was just beyond the capital, and that chapter would be very dark, bloody, and brutal. [...] Those were the worst years for us, and I think certainly the worst for Commander Massoud. [...] Whenever you go back to the years 1992 to 1996, you find this chapter of Afghanistan full of blood. But, why do people call it a \"civil\" war? [...] Unfortunately, Iran was helping one [...] group, Uzbekistan was helping another group, and Pakistan was helping another - Hekmatyar. They made up something like a council of solidarity [...] The Commander [who had been appointed as Afghan minister of defense in 1992 by the peace and power-sharing agreement, the Peshawar Accords,] was almost alone with his own forces. [...] The various forces fighting the government [also established by the Peshawar Accords] were all supported by neighboring countries who had their own interests and wanted us to fight each other [...]\"<ref name=\"Webster University Press Book\"/>\nMasood Khalili again started to work around Massoud as an adviser, interpreter and envoy - \"as a soldier without a gun\" as he calls it himself.<ref name=\"Webster University Press Book\"/> In 1995 Khalili served as the [[Islamic State of Afghanistan]] governments's envoy to Pakistan for President [[Burhanuddin Rabbani]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1995/02/12/world/afghanistan-s-warring-factions-agree-to-form-a-ruling-council.html NY Times: Afghanistan's Warring Factions Agree to Form a Ruling Council]</ref> Relations between the Islamic State of Afghanistan and Pakistan were tense because of the latter's support to [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]] and the [[Taliban]]. In late 1995 Pakistan's government expelled Khalili in what the Washington Post called \"the latest sign of worsening relations between the two countries\".<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/19416437.html?dids=19416437:19416437&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+10%2C+1995&author=&pub=The+Washington+Post+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&desc=Pakistan+Expels+Afghan+Envoy&pqatl=google Washington Post: Pakistan Expels Afghan Envoy]</ref>\n\nOn September 27, 1996, the [[Taliban]] seized power in Kabul with military support by Pakistan and financial support by Saudi Arabia and established the [[Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan]].<ref>Coll, ''Ghost Wars'' (New York: Penguin, 2005), 14.</ref> The Taliban Emirate received no diplomatic recognition from the international community (except from Saudi Arabia, Pakistan and the United Arab Emirates). The United Nations and the international community kept recognition with the [[Islamic State of Afghanistan]] government Masood Khalili was working for. The Taliban imposed on the parts of Afghanistan under their control their political and judicial interpretation of Islam issuing edicts forbidding women to work outside the home, attend school, or to leave their homes unless accompanied by a male relative.<ref name=\"Physicians for Human Rights\">{{cite web |year=1998 |url=http://physiciansforhumanrights.org/library/documents/reports/talibans-war-on-women.pdf |title=The Taliban's War on Women. A Health and Human Rights Crisis in Afghanistan |publisher=[[Physicians for Human Rights]] |access-date=2010-11-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702234326/http://physiciansforhumanrights.org/library/documents/reports/talibans-war-on-women.pdf |archive-date=2007-07-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Physicians for Human Rights (PHR) analyze:\n\n{{blockquote|To PHR\u2019s knowledge, no other regime in the world has methodically and violently forced half of its population into virtual house arrest, prohibiting them on pain of physical punishment.<ref name=\"Physicians for Human Rights\"/>}}\n\nMasood Khalili was not in Kabul during that time but he recalls a phone call he got from Massoud:\n::\"He said: \"Did you hear that we left Kabul?\" \"Yes. Are you okay? Are the others okay?\" \"Yes,\" and he added, \"We'll go back.\" Then he asked: \"Do you have something in mind to tell me?\" [...] I told him a verse of my father's that night:\n:::''Oh the cruel, the despot, the oppressor!''\n:::''I will not indeed be giving that to the one who wants to destroy me.''\n:::''You will see me in another battle, in another time,''\n:::''Because God has given hope to my heart,''\n:::''And this hope will bring me back to what I want to reach.''\n::\"That is what I wanted. Hope will take us back! It's good that you have told me this tonight. Thank you very much.\"\n\nDefense minister Ahmad Shah Massoud created the United Front ([[Northern Alliance]]) in opposition to the Taliban regime. The [[Civil war in Afghanistan (1996-2001)|resistance against the Taliban]] was joined by leaders of all Afghan ethnicities and backgrounds. The Taliban committed massacres killing thousands of civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports98/afghan/Afrepor0-03.htm#P186_38364 |title=INCITEMENT OF VIOLENCE AGAINST HAZARAS BY GOVERNOR NIAZI |accessdate=December 27, 2007 |author= Human Rights Watch|authorlink= Human Rights Watch|date=November 1998|work=AFGHANISTAN: THE MASSACRE IN MAZAR-I SHARIF |publisher= hrw.org}}</ref> As a consequence many civilians fled to the area of [[Ahmad Shah Massoud]].<ref>{{cite web|year=2007 |url=http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/episode/inside-the-taliban-3274/Overview |title=Inside the Taliban |publisher=[[National Geographic Channel|National Geographic]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080929130330/http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/episode/inside-the-taliban-3274/Overview |archivedate=2008-09-29 }}</ref><ref name=\"National Geographic\">{{cite web|year=2007|url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xpQI6HKV-ZY |title = Inside the Taliban| publisher = [[National Geographic Channel|National Geographic]]}}</ref> [[National Geographic Channel|National Geographic]] concluded in its documentary ''\"Inside the Taliban\"'':\n{{blockquote|\"The only thing standing in the way of future Taliban massacres is [[Ahmad Shah Massoud]].\"<ref name=\"National Geographic\"/>}}\nKhalili remained an adviser to [[Ahmad Shah Massoud]].<ref>MacFarquhar, Emily (12 November 1990) \"Praise Allah and pass the ammunition\" ''U.S. News & World Report'' 109(19): p. 54</ref> In 1996 he was appointed as ambassador of the United Front to India.<ref name=\"DT-9-01\">Rashid, Ahmed (11 September 2001) \"Afghanistan resistance leader feared dead in blast\" ''Daily Telegraph'' London, p. 11</ref><ref name=\"TimesIndia01\">Talwar, Ashwani (26 October 2001) \"Khalili Remembers Fatal Attack on Massood\" ''The Times of India''</ref><ref name=\"NYT01\">Dugger, Celia W. (26 October 2001) \"A Nation Challenged: the Survivor: Taliban Foe Tells of Calm, Quiet Assassins\" ''The New York Times'' p. B-2</ref>\n\n==September 9, 2001==\nIn September 2001, while preparing against planned offensives by the Taliban in Takhar province, Ahmed Shah Massoud asked Masood Khalili to come over to [[Takhar]] to advise him.<ref name=\"CSMonitor\">[http://www.csmonitor.com/2002/0220/p07s01-wosc.html CS Monitor: Myth of Masood endures in Afghan halls of power]</ref>\n\nSpeaking to BBC correspondent [[Lyse Doucet]] Masood Khalili recalled the morning of the 9th of September 2001:\n\n::\"The night before that [the assassination] we talked for about three-four hours until 3.30 in the morning. Around that time he told me, Let us open the book and see what will happen - a poetry book that he had, he opened it - it's a kind of telling fortune, from [[Hafez]], the great poet, [[Iran|Persian]] poet. And mostly in Afghanistan we open his book and see what happens to our future. And then I opened it and it came that ... 'Take out from your heart all the siblings of enmity, plant the tree and seed of love - Tonight you two are together. Valuate, many nights go, many days disappear. You two will not be able to see each other again'.<ref name =\"BBC Radio 4\">''One to One'' interview with Lyse Doucet, Tuesday 11th October 2011, BBC Radio 4</ref>\n\nElsewhere he recalls:\n\n::\"The ... morning around ten he came to my room. My passport was lying on the bed. He told me to put my passport in my shirt pocket. [...] We went to the river that divides central Asia and Afghanistan, the Amu Darya. He told me two Arabs were there for an interview. ... We went in and he was on my left. The cameraman was in front of us. I remember the pious smile of the photographer ... And after five minutes he died and I survived.\"<ref name=\"The Orange County Register\">[http://www.afghanrelief.org/pdf/Lynch2003.pdf Tulips in a Minefield] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724225131/http://www.afghanrelief.org/pdf/Lynch2003.pdf |date=2011-07-24 }}</ref>\nOn September 9, 2001, Khalili interpreted for Massoud while he was interviewed by two Tunisians allegedly belonging to [[Al Qaeda]] posing as journalists.<ref name=\"TimesIndia01\"/><ref name=\"NYT01\"/><ref>Anderson, Jon Lee (10 June 2002) \"The Assassins: Who was involved in the murder of Ahmed Shah Massoud?\" ''The New Yorker''</ref> During the interview the suicide assassins detonated a bomb hidden in the video camera.<ref name=\"DT-9-01\"/><ref name=\"TimesIndia01\"/><ref name=\"NYT01\"/><ref name=\"NYT01\"/><ref name =\"CNN\">[http://archives.cnn.com/2001/WORLD/asiapcf/central/10/06/bindra.focus/ Witness recalls assassination of anti-Taliban leader]</ref> Ahmad Shah Massoud died in a helicopter that was taking him and Khalili to hospital. Another aide of Massoud also died in the attack. The ''Los Angeles Times'' writes: \"The explosion left Khalili blind in his right eye, deaf in his right ear and badly burned over much of his body, which was peppered by about 1,000 pieces of shrapnel. About 300 pieces are still in his left leg.\"<ref name=\"LA Times\">[http://articles.latimes.com/2002/sep/11/nation/na-911khalili11LA Times: Masood Khalili]</ref> \nThe passport, which Massoud had told him to put into his shirt pocket, had stopped eight pieces of shrapnel from entering Khalili's heart and had thereby saved his life. \n::\"God saved me, but always God is helped by some means.\"<ref name=\"The Orange County Register\"/>\nAbout the death of Massoud he said:\n::\"When you are buried in the hearts of the people, you are always alive.\"\n::\"Whenever you fight for the right cause, if you die, you don't die. But if you fight for the wrong cause, you never live.\"<ref name=\"The Orange County Register\"/>\nTwo days later the attacks of September 11, 2001, killed 3000 people on U.S. soil.\n\n==Recent Activities==\nAfter the fall of the Taliban regime Masood Khalili served as the ambassador of [[Afghanistan]] to India from 2001 to 2006.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.afghan-web.com/politics/embassies.html |title=\"Embassies of Afghanistan\" |access-date=2008-01-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902035655/http://www.afghan-web.com/politics/embassies.html |archive-date=2011-09-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2007 he was appointed as ambassador to Turkey.<ref name=\"\u00e4fghan web\">[http://www.afghan-web.com/bios/today/others.html#Mkhalili] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026121324/http://www.afghan-web.com/bios/today/others.html#Mkhalili |date=2016-10-26 }} Afghan Web: Other Important Personalities of Today]</ref> To promote the Afghan Culture, Khalili recently translated a book of poems of his father [[Khalilullah Khalili|Ustad Khalilullah Khalili]] into English.<ref>[http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/english/lifestyle/11101961.asp?scr=1 \u2019Assembly of Moths\u2019 by Afghan poet now in Turkish]</ref> About the presence of foreign troops in Afghanistan he said in 2008:\n::\"[T]hose boys give their lives for Afghanistan; a boy from America, Holland, France giving his life, we always admire him. [...] I wish he [Massoud] could be alive today, to see the world is now helping Afghanistan.\"<ref name=\"afghanistanhelp\">[https://groups.yahoo.com/group/afghanistanhelp/message/161 Massoud Khalili at Massoud gathering: \"Afghanistanis admire Dutch soldiers\"]</ref>\n\nAbout the struggle of his country he stated in 2006:\n\n::\"[W]e should not again be interfered with, covertly or overtly, by any neighbouring country. They have the potential to destabilise us. If that is stopped, leave the country to the Afghans. We will make many mistakes but ultimately we will come through. [...] Give us time. After 25 years of war, at least give us 20 years to stand again. This is not easy. The people want to live in peace. Help us with our economy, just so that we can stand again. [...] For 25 years people have seen war. They have lost 1.5 million people. Imagine it -- the pain of the loss of a brother, the loss of a son. We have a phrase that you will never know the fire as long as you are not in it. May God not put any country in the fire that we were in.\"<ref>[http://in.rediff.com/news/2006/feb/03inter1.htm 'May God not put any country in the fire that we were in']</ref>\n\nKhalili was later appointed Afghan ambassador to Spain in 2010. In August 2019 he was mugged on the street in [[Barcelona]] suffering a leg injury while in the city to attend celebrations marking Afghanistan's Independence Day.<ref name=\"pajhwok\">[https://www.pajhwok.com/en/2019/08/20/afghan-ambassador-mugged-barcelona Afghan ambassador mugged in Barcelona\"]</ref> His \u20ac17,000 watch was stolen as part of a significant increase in aggressive petty thefts in the city.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.majorcadailybulletin.com/news/international/2019/08/22/57281/alert-from-the-embassy-due-crime-barcelona.html|title=Alert from the U.S. Embassy due to crime in Barcelona|accessdate=22 August 2019|publisher=Majorca Daily Bulletin}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<!--<nowiki> \nSee http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes for an explanation of how to generate footnotes using the <ref> and </ref> tags.\n</nowiki>-->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{YouTube|NwrAcbHBMXc|Masood Khalili at the 7th death anniversary of Ahmad Shah Massoud}} video\n*{{YouTube|N667V8Y6oNQ|Masood Khalili interpreting between Ahmad Shah Massoud and Javier Solana (EU)}} video\n*{{YouTube|JLsbavEJCTM|Ahmad Shah Massoud with a delegation of Afghan national unity (including Masood Khalili) in Europe 2001}} video\n*[http://www.jezail.org/02_dreamsmith2001/31AF_KLILI.html \"Massoud Khalili 1988\"] photo and commentary\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{AfghanDiplomats}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khalili, Masood}}\n[[Category:Afghan politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Afghan Tajik people]]\n[[Category:People from Parwan Province]]\n[[Category:Afghan expatriates in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Afghanistan to India]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Afghanistan to Turkey]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Afghanistan to Spain]]\n", "name_user": "Sinaloa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Masoud_Khalili"}
{"title_page": "Rick Fitts", "text_new": "{{short description|American television and film actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Notability|Biographies|date=April 2020}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         =   \n| image        =\n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = \n| birth_date   = \n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| occupation   = Actor\n| years_active = \n| spouse       =  \n}}\n'''Rick Fitts''' is an American [[television]] and [[film]] actor.\n\nFitts has had roles in almost a hundred different television shows since his acting debut in 1980, in shows such as ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'', ''[[Knight Rider (1982 TV series)|Knight Rider]]'', ''[[Simon & Simon]]'', ''[[The A-Team]]'', ''[[Hill Street Blues]]'', ''[[Jake and the Fatman]]'', [[Diagnosis Murder]], ''[[Star Trek: Voyager]]'', ''[[Get a Life (TV series)|Get a Life]]'', ''[[Seinfeld]]'', ''[[NYPD Blue]]'', ''[[Reba (TV series)|Reba]]'', ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'', ''[[Frasier]]'', ''[[Commander in Chief (TV series)|Commander in Chief]]'', ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]'', and ''[[Back to You (TV series)|Back to You]]''. He is best known to [[soap opera]] fans for playing the role of ruthless businessman Martin Jackson in ''[[Generations (U.S. TV series)|Generations]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Company|first=Johnson Publishing|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=t70DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA60&lpg=PA60&dq=Rick+Fitts+generations&source=bl&ots=vU7KiszTZn&sig=ACfU3U1_yrPLaeLqCe3WBewAaykdJ2K0gA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiLzMOUn8_oAhU1oXEKHc-UDjA4ChDoATAFegQIDBA3#v=onepage&q=Rick%20Fitts%20generations&f=false|title=Jet|date=1989-04-03|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company|language=en}}</ref> He has also worked in voiceover, supplying the voice of Mr. Johanssen in the animated series ''[[Hey Arnold!]]''\n\nHe has also appeared in several minor roles in films, mostly for [[television movie]]s.\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0280109}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fitts, Rick}}\n[[Category:American male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{US-screen-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American television and film actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Notability|Biographies|date=April 2020}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         =   \n| image        =\n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = \n| birth_date   = \n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| occupation   = Actor\n| years_active = \n| spouse       =  \n}}\n'''Rick Fitts''' is an American [[television]] and [[film]] actor.\n\nFitts has had roles in almost a hundred different television shows since his acting debut in 1980, in shows such as ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'', ''[[Knight Rider (1982 TV series)|Knight Rider]]'', ''[[Simon & Simon]]'', ''[[The A-Team]]'', ''[[Hill Street Blues]]'', ''[[Jake and the Fatman]]'', [[Diagnosis Murder]], ''[[Star Trek: Voyager]]'', ''[[Get a Life (TV series)|Get a Life]]'', ''[[Seinfeld]]'', ''[[NYPD Blue]]'', ''[[Reba (TV series)|Reba]]'', ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'', ''[[Frasier]]'', ''[[Commander in Chief (TV series)|Commander in Chief]]'', ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]'', and ''[[Back to You (TV series)|Back to You]]''. He is best known to [[soap opera]] fans for playing the role of ruthless businessman Martin Jackson in ''[[Generations (U.S. TV series)|Generations]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Company|first=Johnson Publishing|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=t70DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA60&lpg=PA60&dq=Rick+Fitts+generations&source=bl&ots=vU7KiszTZn&sig=ACfU3U1_yrPLaeLqCe3WBewAaykdJ2K0gA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiLzMOUn8_oAhU1oXEKHc-UDjA4ChDoATAFegQIDBA3#v=onepage&q=Rick%20Fitts%20generations&f=false|title=Jet|date=1989-04-03|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company|language=en}}</ref> He has also worked in voiceover, supplying the voice of Mr. Johanssen in the animated series ''[[Hey Arnold!]]''\n\nHe has also appeared in several minor roles in films, mostly for [[television movie]]s.\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0280109}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fitts, Rick}}\n[[Category:American male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{US-screen-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cardiffbear88", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rick_Fitts"}
{"title_page": "Majid yousefy", "text_new": "{{db-person}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Majid Yousefy\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1992|4|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Tehran]], Iran\n| nationality  = [[Iran|Iranian]]\n| education    = Journalism ([[Journalism]])\n| occupation   = [[Journalist]], [[writer]], [[Film producer]], [[Singing]]\n| alma_mater   = [[Iran Broadcasting University]]\n| years_active = 2001\u2013present\n| website      = https://persianagroup.tv/\n}}\nMajid Yousefi (born 1992 in [[Isfahan]]) is a [[journalist]], [[writer]], [[singer]] and [[producer]] of Iran Radio and Television. He is a graduate student of [[Journalism]] from the [[Iran Broadcasting University]]. He is the founder of [[Persiana]].<ref>http://persianagroup.tv/archives/84</ref>\n\n\n==Sources==\n<references />\n", "text_old": "{{db-person}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Majid Yousefy\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1992|4|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Tehran]], Iran\n| nationality  = [[Iran|Iranian]]\n| education    = Journalism ([[Journalism]])\n| occupation   = [[Journalist]], [[writer]], [[Film producer]], [[Singing]]\n| alma_mater   = [[Iran Broadcasting University]]\n| years_active = 2001\u2013present\n| website      = https://persianagroup.tv/\n}}\nMajid Yousefi (born 1992 in [[Isfahan]]) is a [[journalist]], [[writer]], [[singer]] and [[producer]] of Iran Radio and Television. He is a graduate student of [[Journalism]] from the [[Iran Broadcasting University]]. He is the founder of [[Persiana]].<ref>http://persianagroup.tv/archives/84</ref>\n", "name_user": "Somayye95", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Majid_yousefy"}
{"title_page": "Christopher H. Browne", "text_new": "'''Christopher H. Browne''' (1946 &ndash; December 13, 2009) was a famous [[value investor]].<ref name=\"WSJ\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703438404574598442025375858 |title=A Career Spent Finding Value  |first=Jason |last=Zweig |date=16 December 2009 |publisher=Wall Street Journal}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nHe graduated from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in 1969 with a B.A. in history.<ref name=\"THEDP\">{{Cite news |url=http://thedp.com/article/u-trustee-browne-died-62 |first=Jared |last=McDonald |date=15 December 2009 |title=U. Trustee Browne died at 62 |publisher=Daily Pennsylvanian }}</ref>\n\n===Career===\nHe started his career at the firm [[Tweedy, Browne]], a favorite brokerage firm among prominent value investors like [[Benjamin Graham]] and [[Warren Buffett]].<ref name=\"WSJ\"/> His success as an investor and shareholder, who held business management accountable, was renowned. For example, since their inception in 1993, both Tweedy, Browne's Value and Global Value Funds have outperformed market averages.<ref name=\"WSJ\"/> Also, as a shareholder, he was the first to publicly suspect [[Conrad Black]]'s dubious lavish spending and embezzlement from [[Sun-Times Media Group|Hollinger]]. Browne was often known as one of the best value investors ever.<ref name=\"WSJ\"/>\n\nIn 2006 he authored a book, ''[[The Little Book of Value Investing]]'', in order to teach ordinary investors how to value invest.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-0470055898.html |title=Wiley: The Little Book of Value Investing |publisher=Wiley |accessdate=18 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy===\nHe donated $25 million to establish several endowed professorships at the [[University of Pennsylvania]], where he was a trustee, including the professorships held by [[Amy Gutmann]] and [[Rogers Smith]].<ref name=\"THEDP\"/> Upon his death, Christopher Browne was survived by his partner, Andrew S. Gordon, who then died on September 7, 2013.<ref>{{Cite journal |title=In Memoriam Christopher H. Browne: 1946-2009  |journal=Penn Arts & Sciences Magazine |issue=Fall/Winter 2009 |page=32 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Browne, Christopher H}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:American investors]]\n[[Category:LGBT businesspeople from the United States]]\n\n\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n", "text_old": "'''Christopher H. Browne''' (1946 &ndash; December 13, 2009) was a famous [[value investor]].<ref name=\"WSJ\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703438404574598442025375858 |title=A Career Spent Finding Value  |first=Jason |last=Zweig |date=16 December 2009 |publisher=Wall Street Journal}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nHe graduated from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in 1969 with a B.A. in history.<ref name=\"THEDP\">{{Cite news |url=http://thedp.com/article/u-trustee-browne-died-62 |first=Jared |last=McDonald |date=15 December 2009 |title=U. Trustee Browne died at 62 |publisher=Daily Pennsylvanian }}</ref>\n\n===Career===\nHe started his career at the firm [[Tweedy, Browne]], a favorite brokerage firm among prominent value investors like [[Benjamin Graham]] and [[Warren Buffett]].<ref name=\"WSJ\"/> His success as an investor and shareholder, who held business management accountable, was renowned. For example, since their inception in 1993, both Tweedy, Browne's Value and Global Value Funds have outperformed market averages.<ref name=\"WSJ\"/> Also, as a shareholder, he was the first to publicly suspect [[Conrad Black]]'s dubious lavish spending and embezzlement from [[Sun-Times Media Group|Hollinger]]. Browne was often known as one of the best value investors ever.<ref name=\"WSJ\"/>\n\nIn 2006 he authored a book, ''[[The Little Book of Value Investing]]'', in order to teach ordinary investors how to value invest.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-0470055898.html |title=Wiley: The Little Book of Value Investing |publisher=Wiley |accessdate=18 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy===\nHe donated $25 million to establish several endowed professorships at the [[University of Pennsylvania]], where he was a trustee, including the professorships held by [[Amy Gutmann]] and [[Rogers Smith]].<ref name=\"THEDP\"/> Upon his death, Christopher Browne was survived by his partner, Andrew S. Gordon, who then died on September 7, 2013.<ref>{{Cite journal |title=In Memoriam Christopher H. Browne: 1946-2009  |journal=Penn Arts & Sciences Magazine |issue=Fall/Winter 2009 |page=32 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Browne, Christopher H}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:American investors]]\n[[Category:LGBT businesspeople from the United States]]\n\n\n{{US-business-bio-1940s-stub}}\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n", "name_user": "Payaguasrivers", "label": "safe", "comment": "not stub now", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christopher_H._Browne"}
